<DOCNO> XIE19970301.0002 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-28 16:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Disappointed over Iran's Call for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, February 28 (Xinhua) -- Turkey today expressed its
disappointment over Iran's call for the withdrawal of Turkish
Ambassador to Tehran Osman Koruturk and Consul General in
Orumieh Ufuk Ozsancak, a Turkish Foreign Ministry statement said.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that Iranian Ambassador Muhammed Reza
Baqeri with his speech in Sincan on February 1 and Iranian
Consul General in Istanbul Muhammed Reza Rasheed with his
statement to a news agency seriously violated international
principles of law.
</P>
<P>
Baqeri made a controversial speech on the occasion of marking
"Al-quds (Jerusalem) Night," an Iran-promoted anti-Israel event
in Sincan, 40 kilometers west of Ankara.
</P>
<P>
Baqeri's remarks angered the Turkish Foreign Ministry, which
lodged a protest note against him, saying that he should not
comment on Turkey's internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Embassy in Tehran later made initiatives to the
Iranian Foreign Ministry and called on the withdrawal of the two
Iranian diplomats, said the statement.
</P>
<P>
Baqeri and Rasheed departed Turkey for home on February 19.
</P>
<P>
The statement added that Iranian Charge d'affaires here said
that within the framework of an order from Iran, he called for
the withdrawal of Koruturk and Ozsancak as they could not
function in Iran any more.
</P>
<P>
The statement pointed out that Turkey's call for the
withdrawal of the Iranian diplomats has strong and objective
reasons in accordance with international law and norms.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, the Turkish Foreign Ministry declared Saeed
Zadeh, Iranian consul general in Erzurum, a city in eastern
Turkey, as persona non grata and asked him to leave Turkey within
48 hours.
</P>
<P>
Turkey made the tough decision as Zadeh, through a Turkish
private news agency and some television channels Wednesday,
accused Turkish Second Chief of General Staff Cevik Bir of
making "unfriendly" speeches against Iran in Washington.
</P>
<P>
Bir called Iran a supporter of terrorism during a joint
U.S.-Turkish Council meeting in the United States.
</P>
<P>
Iran issued a protest Monday, saying that what Bir said was
"irresponsible, unacceptable and similar to those by the U.S. and
Israel." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
