<HEADLINE> Second-oldest Canadian Retailer Claims Bankruptcy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, February 28 (Xinhua) -- A time-honored department store
chain of Canada, the T. Eaton's Co. Ltd., has sought and received
bankruptcy protection, reports said today.
</P>
<P>
George Eaton, president of the family-owned company, the
second-oldest retailer in Canada, called the move a "temporary
measure" that will allow Eaton's to keep creditors at bay until it
works out a plan to turn the company around.
</P>
<P>
The company, which claimed insolvency in court documents filed
Thursday in Ontario Court, has until June 15 to file a business
plan and has protection from creditors until June 30.
</P>
<P>
The retailer reportedly owns banks 118 million U.S. dollars
and about the same amount to its suppliers. It has lost close to
190 million dollars since 1988.
</P>
<P>
Eaton's said it would probably close up to 40 of its 87 stores
across Canada and shed a good portion of its 16,000 employees.
</P>
<P>
The company is the latest to suffer from the country's highly
competitive and troubled retail industry, resulting from low
consumer confidence and a sluggish economy.
</P>
<P>
Last September, the retailing Consumers Distributing Inc. went
bankrupt after failing to manage its 190-million-dollar debt.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
