<HEADLINE> UK Prime Minister Defiant After By-Election Defeat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, February 28 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister John
Major said today after his party losing a key by-election that the
Tories would still be returned to power.
</P>
<P>
However, he said in an interview with ITN television that "if
opinion does not change, then we are going to have a Labor
government."
</P>
<P>
On an unusually high turnout for a by-election of 73 percent,
Labor candidate Ben Chapman received 22,767 votes in Wirral South,
7,888 votes more than the 14,879 of his Conservative rival Les
Byrom.
</P>
<P>
Immediately knowing the result, a Labor spokesman said, "No
party has ever lost a by-election so close to a general election,
in a seat they had won at the previous general election, and gone
on to win the general election."
</P>
<P>
Labor's deputy leader John Prescott said the result was "a
major shift in politics."
</P>
<P>
Liberal Democratic Party leader Paddy Ashdown asked Prime
Minister Major to call an election. "The longer you leave it, the
harder you fall," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
