<DOCNO> XIE19970301.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Economic Growth in 4th Quarter Revised Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 28 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. economy grew at a
quick 3.9 percent annual rate in the fourth quarter of 1996, but
much slower than the first estimated rate announced last month.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Commerce Department revised down today the economic
expansion in the last three months of 1996 from the initial
estimate of a seasonally adjusted 4.7 percent growth rate.
</P>
<P>
The down revision of 0.8 percentage points produced a change in
the growth estimate for all of 1996, pulling it down to 2.4
percent from 2.5 percent, the Commerce Department report said.
</P>
<P>
The revision in the gross domestic product (GDP), the economy's
total output of goods and services, was almost entirely due to a
slower buildup in inventories of unsold goods, according to the
report.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that a slimmer backlog of surplus stocks means
that any pickup in consumer demand is more likely to create
production increases at the nation's factories.
</P>
<P>
Consumer spending, which accounts for roughly two-thirds of the
U.S. economic activity, rose at a 3.4 percent annual rate.
</P>
<P>
In other areas, business investment in new plant and equipment
grew at a 5.5 percent annual rate. Residential construction, a key
source of strength in the first half of 1996, edged lower at a 0.4
percent rate in the final quarter.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. trade deficit, which had detracted from economic
growth during the first nine months of the year, added 37.4
billion dollars to growth in the last three months.
</P>
<P>
The report said measure of inflation tied to GDP -- prices paid
by U.S. residents -- rose at a moderate 2.5 percent annual rate in
the October-December period, the same as first estimated.
</P>
<P>
Last year's growth marked an improvement over the 2 percent
registered in 1995 but was much slower than the robust 3.5 percent
advance in 1994, the best in six years.
</P>
<P>
The final revision to the U.S. economic growth rate is expected
next month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
