<HEADLINE> Angolan Envoy Reports Slow Progress on Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, February 28 (Xinhua) -- Angolan president Jose Eduardo
Dos Santos today sent a special message to Zimbabwean president
Robert Mugabe briefing him on latest developments on the peace
process in Angola.
</P>
<P>
The message was delivered by Dos Santos' special envoy Lopo Do
Nascimento to Mugabe at Zimbabwe house in Harare. Mugabe chairs
the southern African development community's organ on politics,
defence and security.
</P>
<P>
"The peace process is going on but very, very slowly... and
the problem is with UNITA," Nascimento told journalists after
meeting Mugabe.
</P>
<P>
He said UNITA has not yet dispatched its four members to join
the national unity and reconciliation cabinet heading the
ministries of tourism, commerce, health and mines.
</P>
<P>
Establishment of the government, scheduled for January 25, was
postponed after negotiators failed to find an acceptable role for
Savimbi, who still controls much of Angola, including
diamond-rich areas in the northeast.
</P>
<P>
Savimbi has rejected a MPLA offer to become vice-president in
a national unity government demanding he be made the official
leader of the opposition in parliament or a special adviser to
Dos Santos. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
