<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Editorial Hails Opening of NPC Annual Session (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 28 (Xinhua) -- China's leading newspaper,
People's Daily, will carry an editorial, hailing the opening of
the annual session of the National People's Congress (NPC),
China's legislature.
</P>
<P>
The editorial notes that the Fifth Session of the Eighth NPC,
which is convened shortly after the Chinese people suffered the
loss of their beloved Deng Xiaoping and in this important year in
the history of China, is of an extraordinary significance, and has
arrested the attention of the world.
</P>
<P>
During the session, the editorial says, NPC deputies will hear
and review the government report, examine and approve reports on
the implementation of the 1996 plan for national economic and
social development and budget, the draft plan for national
economic and social development and budget in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Also heard and examined will be a Draft Criminal Law and a
Draft National Defence Law, a motion on the establishment of the
centrally-administered Chongqing municipality, work reports of the
NPC Standing Committee, the Supreme People's Court and the Supreme
Procuratorate.
</P>
<P>
The deputies will perform their rights empowered by the
constitution and laws to air views on matters of national
importance as a way to help realize the goals set forth in the
Ninth Five-Year Plan and Long-Range Objectives Through the Year
2010, thus making new contributions to the cause of building
socialism with Chinese characteristics pioneered by Deng Xiaoping,
the editorial says.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the first year for the Ninth Five-Year Plan and
Long-Range Objectives Through the Year 2010, people of various
ethnic groups went all out to score new achievements in reform,
opening-up and modernization drive, ensuring a good beginning for
the trans-century target, the editorial says.
</P>
<P>
Specifically, the country maintained rapid economic growth,
along with effective control of inflation, steady progress with
economic restructuring, furthering opening up to the outside
world, and fresh achievements in science and technology, education
and various social undertakings, the editorial cites.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
