<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Existing Home Sales Increase in January </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 28 (Xinhua) -- Sales of previously owned
homes in the U.S. increased by 2.1 percent in January following a
banner year in 1996, the U.S. National Association of Realtors
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The report said that previously owned single-family homes sold
at a 3.94 million annual rate last month, up from a 3.86 million
rate in December,
</P>
<P>
Russell K. Booth, the Realtors' president, said that the
increase resulted from warm temperatures and low mortgage rates in
the month.
</P>
<P>
Regionally, existing home sales rose by 8.4 percent in the West
and 3.6 percent in the South. But the sales fell by 1 percent in
the Midwest and 4.8 percent in the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
The national median price of an existing home in the U.S. was
120,500 dollars last month, up 5 percent from a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
For all of 1996, existing home sales in the U.S. totaled 4.08
million, the best in 18 years. The sharp increase of sales last
year was spurred by moderate economic growth and relatively low
mortgage rates. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970301.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Data Poverty Hampers Intra-African Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, February 28 (Xinhua) -- Increased intra-African trade
is being hampered by lack of adequate information about existing
commercial opportunities, an international trade expert said
today.
</P>
<P>
In a paper presented at a two-day meeting organised by the
COMESA bankers association in Harare, Carlo Cattani, senior
adviser on trade financing at the Geneva-based international
trade centre, said such lack of information was hampering efforts
to redirect trade flows from traditional partners in the west.
</P>
<P>
"It is usually easier to gather information on business
opportunities, market access conditions and rules and regulations
concerning industrialised countries than about your neighbouring
country," Cattani told the meeting, which is discussing
international trade finance.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, which ends today, has been called to discuss ways
of facilitating intra-African trade through different financing
mechanisms.
</P>
<P>
Cattani said experience had shown that it was often difficult
for many african firms to trade with their partners from the
region than with major markets abroad because relevant trade
information was scarce.
</P>
<P>
"Such lack of information has the effect of reinforcing the
trade flows directed to traditional partners in the north, at the
disadvantage of profitable intra-African trade opportunities," he
said.
</P>
<P>
He said another major constraint was the lack of cheap
finance, as evidence showed that banks and other credit
institutions preferred to assist companies from the west rather
than African countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
