<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada's Economy Grows 1.5 Percent in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, February 28 (Xinhua) -- Canada's real gross domestic
product (GDP) grew 0.7 percent in the fourth quarter of 1996,
bringing the annual growth rate to a modest 1.5 percent,
Statistics Canada reported today.
</P>
<P>
The fourth quarter of 1996 was the second consecutive quarter
of relatively strong growth after six weak quarters. The real GDP
was 2.3 percent above the fourth quarter level of 1995.
</P>
<P>
"While growth was relatively weak throughout 1995 and the first
quarters of 1996, economic activity picked up significantly in the
second half of 1996," the federal agency said.
</P>
<P>
Its figures show that real GDP growth for the fourth quarters
of 1996 was 0.3, 0.4, 0.8 and 0.7 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
"The sources of strength were equally balanced between domestic
and foreign demand," the agency said. For the year, merchandise
exports increased 4.6 percent, while imports rose 5.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, Canada saw notable increases in investment in
machinery and equipment (up 11.0 percent), construction (up 11.5
percent) and personal expenditure (up 2.4 percent).
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, government expenditure and non-residential
construction declined 1.8 percent and 3.2 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
During the year, Canada's personal income increased 2.0
percent, while personal income taxes grew by 7.1 percent. "As a
result, disposable income grew by only 1.0 percent," the agency
noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970301.0025 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HKSAR Government Has a Good Start, Says Tung Chee Hwa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, February 28 (Xinhua) -- With the setting up of the
Executive Council and the appointment of principal officials for
its first government, the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region
(HKSAR) government has made a good start, SAR's Chief Executive
Tung Chee Hwa said here today.
</P>
<P>
"I should thank the Chinese central government for absolutely
trusting me and enabling me to make the appointments smoothly,"
Tung said, adding, There has been a very positive response to
these appointments.
</P>
<P>
Tung was speaking at a diner given in his honor by the Stock
Exchange of Hong Kong, the Hong Kong Futures Exchange, the Chinese
 Gold and Silver Exchange Society and the Hong Kong Securities
Clearing Company.
</P>
<P>
Tung said he believed the people of Hong Kong have, as he has,
full confidence in a smooth handover of Hong Kong and that the
future of Hong Kong "is very bright indeed."
</P>
<P>
In the coming months, a series of laws and appointments which
have to take effective after the handover, will be discussed and
proposed to the Provisional Legislature for approval. He would
make some appointments according to the regulations of the Basic
Law, Tung said.
</P>
<P>
A commission is soon to be set up according to the Basic Law
for the recommendation of judicial appointments. And based on the
commission's recommendations, the Chief Executive will appoint
persons for the Court of Final Appeal and the Chief Justice for
the High Court.
</P>
<P>
Tung said he will also appoint, according to the decisions of
the Preparatory Committee and the laws to be passed by the
Provisional Legislature, regional councilors.
</P>
<P>
The starting point for his work would be the long-term and
overall interests of the six million people of Hong Kong, Tung
said.
</P>
<P>
"The SAR government has a lot of serious work to do and a lot
of pressing matters to deal with, so I will definitely not allow
short-time fluctuations in public options to affect my work," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Tung said that some overseas investors, influenced by
inaccurate reporting in the Western media and by remarks made by
some Hong Kong persons outside Hong Kong, said they would reassess
 their interest to invest in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Tung called on his audience to let more people outside Hong
Kong to know what is happening here.
</P>
<P>
"We do have a duty to enable the general public outside Hong
Kong to have an objective understanding of the reality in Hong
Kong," Tung said.
</P>
<P>
The Chief Executive said he had decided to visit some
countries, first the United States, to clarify some
misunderstandings of the real situation in Hong Kong.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970301.0026 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jiang Calls for Doing a Good Job with, HK, Macao Affairs (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In more than 100 days, he said, Hong Kong will return to the
embrace of the motherland, and six million Hong Kong compatriots
will exercise the democratic rights as masters of their own
destiny.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's return to the motherland signifies the end of over
one-century-old national humiliation for the Chinese people, and
another major step in the course of achieving national
reunification.
</P>
<P>
He added that Macao will also return to the embrace of the
motherland in 1999, which is a great event shining through the
history of the Chinese nation. All the Chinese people, including
Hong Kong and Macao compatriots, are encouraged and inspired.
</P>
<P>
On behalf of the CPC Central Committee, the State Council and
people across China, Jiang expressed his gratitude to the members
for the contributions they had made in promoting Hong Kong and
Macao's successful return to the motherland and smooth transition
of power, maintaining Hong Kong and Macao's prosperity and
stability, and helping to promote the motherland's reform and
opening-up and modernization drive.
</P>
<P>
The successful settlement of the historical problems of Hong
Kong and Macao by peaceful means is that "we have unswervingly
adhered to the important principles and policies defined personally by
Comrade Deng Xiaoping.
</P>
<P>
The concept of "one country, two systems" is an integral
part of the theory of building socialism with Chinese
characteristics, and the unique, major contribution by Comrade
Deng Xiaoping to the accomplishment of the great cause of the
motherland's reunification.
</P>
<P>
It not only chartered the correct path and provide the basic
guarantee for the settlement of the Hong Kong, Macao and Taiwan
issues, but provided a fine example for the settlement of similar
problems internationally left over from history, said Jiang.
</P>
<P>
Although Comrade Xiaoping has left us, he pledged, the basic
line of "one focus, two basic points" and a series of major
principles and policies he set forth will be adhered to
unswervingly, and the great cause of building socialism with
Chinese characteristics be implemented steadfastly.
</P>
<P>
"We must carry forward at Comrade Xiaoping's behest, and follow
the principles and policies he set forth for keeping long-term
prosperity and stability in Hong Kong and an do a good job with
Hong Kong and Macao affairs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
