<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China, Uganda Agree on Extnding Period of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, February 28 (Xinhua) -- China and Uganda have signed
an agreement on extending the period of Uganda's utilisation of
an interest-free loan of 50 million renminbi (over 6 million U.S.
dollars), provided by China in accordance with an agreement
between the two countries signed on March 24, 1989.
</P>
<P>
The visiting Chinese Assistant Minister of Foreign Trade and
Economic Cooperation Yang Wensheng and Ugandan Minister of
Finance Mayanja Nkangi signed the agreement on behalf of their
respective government here today.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, the Chinese gopvernment will extend the
utilisation period of the loan from June 30, 1994 to June 30,
1998, and the payment of the loan shall be handled in accordance
with the stipulations as specified in the agreement between the
governments of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Present at the funaction were Chinese Ambassador to Uganda Tan
Xingju and some officials in Ugandan Ministry of Finance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970301.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greek PM Holds Talks With NATO Chief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, February 28 (Xinhua) -- Greek Prime Minister Costas
Simitis today held talks with NATO Secretary General Javier Solana
focusing on the tension in Greek-Turkish relations and efforts to
restructure the alliance.
</P>
<P>
Simitis first held private talks with Solana, the meeting
subsequently being attended by Foreign Minister Theodoros Pangalos
and Defense Minister Akis Tsohatzopoulos.
</P>
<P>
According to informed sources, Solana's proposals for defusing
the tension in Greek-Turkish relations were discussed at length.
</P>
<P>
Solana said that what was important was to work on the issue
before the NATO summit on July 8-9.
</P>
<P>
The same sources said during today's talks Solana underlined
that in view of the forthcoming NATO enlargement, the problems
which exist between alliance members must be dealt with.
</P>
<P>
The sources said Solana appeared to insist on his proposal
concerning an extension of the moratorium on Greek and Turkish
military exercises in the Aegean during the summer months.
</P>
<P>
At the present time, the sources said, the Greek side does not
appear willing to discuss the issue, given Ankara's general stance
towards Athens.
</P>
<P>
For this reason Solana intends to return to Greece and Turkey
after the July NATO summit while insisting that a solution be
found by July.
</P>
<P>
Solana described his talks here as "extremely constructive"
since he had ascertained that Greece's positions were very
positive concerning the building of the new NATO, in a reference
to proposed new military structures, new missions, new members and
the alliance's new relationship with Russia.
</P>
<P>
In these sectors, Simitis underlined that important decisions
must be taken at the Madrid summit in July, and he added that
talks would continue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
