<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WHO Vows to Reduce Maternal Morbidity by 50 Pct by 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, February 28 (Xinhua) -- Deaths of women in childbirth
or during unacceptable abortion methods continue at a rate of
close to 600,000 a year, the World Health Organization (WHO) said
here today.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting held at the WHO headquarters in Geneva Monday and
Tuesday, the Fifth Global Commission for Women's Health (GCWH) set
out a comprehensive agenda on the issue of maternal morbidity. WHO
has set a target of reducing maternal morbidity by 50 percent by
the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
"It is unacceptable and shameful that women die in childbirth
today," said Hillary Rodham Clinton, First Lady of the United
States of America, in a special message to the GCWH.
</P>
<P>
Mrs Clinton pointed out that since the women's conference in
Beijing in 1995, there have been tangible accomplishments in
important areas of women's health. She cited the elimination of
the practice of female genital mutilation in Egypt and guarantees
of stay for mothers in U.S. hospitals as concrete examples of a
change in health care practices.
</P>
<P>
In its press release, WHO also listed important progress made
on other key issues: increased literacy and reducing anemia.
</P>
<P>
Noting that many of the health problems of women and young
girls can be solved by literacy and education, the delegates
endorsed WHO plans to hold a top level roundtable discussion with
the United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural
Organization (UNESCO) on the subject of "Education for the
Promotion of Health in Women and Girls."
</P>
<P>
Anemia is one of the greatest threats to the health of women of
child-bearing age around the world. Studies indicate that iron
deficiency is prevalent on every continent. Who's objective is to
reduce this significant health problem by one third by the year
2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970301.0036 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Investors Pour More Money Into Mutual Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The tremendous fund investing in January far surpassed the 24
billion U.S. dollars that the mutual-fund industry's trade group
had predicted and handily beat the record of 28.9 billion monthly
inflow set in January a year ago, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
But some analysts expressed their worries about duration of the
influx of funds. The Federal Reserve chairman has twice warned now
that the stock market may be rising too fast.
</P>
<P>
But there's no evidence the deluge will ease soon, the paper
said. Fund executives say February is turning out to be a massive
month, too, though it likely won't match the rate of inflow during
January. Large-company funds, growth-and-income funds and in
particular index funds are taking in lots of cash, as investors
pursue soaring big company stocks.
</P>
<P>
Not all the money is going into stock funds in the U.S., the
paper said. But the 23.4 billion U.S. dollars that poured into
U.S. stock funds in January was a record, according to the
Investment Company Institute. The second biggest month for U.S.
stock funds was last May, when such funds took in a bit more than
21 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
A lot of the money in January was new money to the stock
market and helped sustain the continued rise in stock prices,
according to the report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
