<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-28 18:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Not to Overproduce Oil After Lift of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, February 28 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi Oil Minister Amir
Mohammed Rashid said here today that his country will not
overproduce oil after the U.N.-imposed sanctions are lifted.
</P>
<P>
At a news conference held at the Oil Ministry, Rashid said
Iraq will not overproduce oil and will observe strictly the OPEC
quota.
</P>
<P>
"Our leadership is very responsible for the stability of the
oil market and its prices, because overproduction will do harm
to the oil market as well as the iraqi people," the minister
said.
</P>
<P>
Iraq plans to raise its oil output to 6 million barrels per
day after the U.N.-imposed sanctions are totally lifted, which
almost doubles the amount of oil produced before the 1991 Gulf
War.
</P>
<P>
When asked whether Iraq will ask for compensation for its
losses during the period of sanctions, Rashid said although
certain OPEC members have been overproducing oil at the expenses
of Iraq, his country has no intention to ask for any
compensation.
</P>
<P>
On cooperation in the development of Iraqi oil fields, the
minister reiterated that Iraq will give priority to those friendly
countries such as France, Russia and China, which support the
Iraqi people and call for the lifting of sanctions imposed on
Iraq more than six years ago.
</P>
<P>
Recently, Iraqi officials and newspapers strongly criticized
U.S. for creating obstacles and deliberately delaying the
implementation of the oil-for-food deal, which allows Iraq to
sell 2 billion dollars worth of oil to buy food and medicine
badly needed in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
