<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 1997 Crucial for Cyprus: EU Commissioner </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, February 28 (Xinhua) -- European Union (EU) External
Relations Commissioner Hans van den Broek said here today that
1997 remains a crucial year for Cyprus and the EU has committed
to assisting efforts toward a Cyprus settlement.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference at the end of his three-day
visit to the island, the EU official said he detected a
willingness to cooperate toward a political settlement on the
part of the Cyprus government.
</P>
<P>
"President Glafcos Clerides has underlined again on several
occasions that he has made efforts for negotiations," the
commissioner said, adding that Clerides also stated he is
prepared to "resume negotiations if there is good preparation
and some convergence of mind that makes it worthwhile to
negotiate."
</P>
<P>
The EU official said he conveyed this message to Turkish
Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash and called on him "to lift the
isolation of his community."
</P>
<P>
The commissioner also reaffirmed the EU commitment that
Cyprus' EU membership negotiations will start unconditionally by
the beginning of 1998.
</P>
<P>
"What we are adding to that now is what boost should be given
to those accession negotiations and how much smoother they could
develop and lead to a successful end in case the political
process here shows the necessary progress", he said.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the issue of Turkish Cypriot participation in
the accession negotiations, the EU commissioner said the EU, as
a whole, would like to see that "circumstances and progress
toward a political settlement will permit an involvement of both
communities in accession talks."
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriot participation, he noted, will depend on the
state of political settlement talks. "If the parties
here could agree to a formula, the EU would not stand in their
way," he added.
</P>
<P>
Hans van den Broek, who arrived here Wednesday, had separate
meetings with President Clerides and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf
Denktash.
</P>
<P>
He said earlier that he came to Cyprus to convey two main
messages: the EU will honor its commitment to the accession
talks, which means that 1998 will be the year when negotiations
begin in earnest, and that 1997 is the year when direct
negotiations on the Cyprus problem under U.N. auspices should
receive the highest priority.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkish troops
occupied the northern third of the island in the wake of an
Athens-backed coup.
</P>
<P>
The Eastern Mediterranean island applied for the full EU
membership in 1990. 
</P>
</TEXT>
