<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada's Current Account Remains in Red in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, February 28 (Xinhua) -- Canada's current account
continued to be in the red in 1996, this time with a deficit of
1.2 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
"Buoyed by a record merchandise trade surplus, Canada's current
account deficit declined for a third consecutive year," Statistics
Canada reported today, saying that the deficit was by far the
lowest level since 1984.
</P>
<P>
It had been expected that Canada would reap a current account
surplus last year.
</P>
<P>
However, lower exports and higher imports in the fourth quarter
reduced Canada's goods surplus to its lowest level in a year and a
half, which rendered the surplus target out of reach.
</P>
<P>
Overall, Canada did quite a good job at exporting last year.
Its surplus on trade in goods climbed to a record high of 25.2
billion dollars, which was 4.5 billion dollars over that of 1995.
</P>
<P>
On the capital account front, the figures show that foreigners
continued to invest in Canadian bonds and stocks. But these
inflows were largely offset by record investment by Canadians in
foreign stocks.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, Canada's deficit on services stood at 6.9 billion
dollars. The deficit on commercial services increased slightly,
and the travel deficit showed a small increase after steadily
narrowing since 1992. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970301.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> W. Bank Urged to Provide Water Technologies to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, February 28 (Xinhua) -- A Kenyan official today
called on the World Bank to provide water harnessing
technologies to combat periodical drought in the country.
</P>
<P>
Wamatu Njoroge, Permanent Secretary of the Ministry of
Research, technical training and technology, was speaking when
World Bank Technical Manager for African region Sushma Ganguly
today paid a courtesy call on him.
</P>
<P>
Both officials agreed that the problem of drought and the
resultant food shortage facing Kenya can be eliminated through
the provision of water harnessing technologies and simple
micro-irrigation systems at farm level.
</P>
<P>
Njoroge noted that although Kenya periodically experienced
severe drought, a lot of rain water was lost and some times
resulted in devastating floods.
</P>
<P>
He called on the World Bank to assist Kenyan farmers in
providing water harnessing technologies to enable them to produce
enough food for domestic consumption and export.
</P>
<P>
In response, Ganguly agreed to actively pursue the request of
fund with the bank's headquarters for the provision of suitable
technologies.
</P>
<P>
The two officials also discussed the implementation of the
National Agricultural Research Project phase two which the World
Bank has provided about 50 million U.S. Dollars credit to Kenya.
</P>
<P>
The project will foster food security, poverty reduction and
environment protection by raising agricultural productivity and
farmers' income through improved technologies.
</P>
<P>
During the phase two, a pilot scheme will develop a
sustainable national seed system that can ensure timely
availability of quality seeds to farmers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
