<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-28 19:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Over 5,000 Investment Projects Set up in Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, February 28 (Xinhua) -- Altogether 5,384 investment
projects have been set up in Egypt by the end of January, a
majority of them formed over the past 15 years since it adopted
the open door policy in 1981.
</P>
<P>
According to a report of the Egyptian General Investment
Authority, these projects have a combined capital of 53.5 billion
Egyptian pounds (15.74 U.S. dollars), creating 624,014 jobs.
</P>
<P>
Among them, 4,512 projects were established in the 1981-96
period, with a combined capital of 11.9 billion dollars. About
440,000 new jobs were created by these projects.
</P>
<P>
The number of projects jumped from 1,599 in 1992 to 4,279 in
1996, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The total Arab contributions to the investment projects
amounted to 1,314 projects, accounting for 24.4 percent of the
total number, with a capital of 23.77 billion pounds (6.99
billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
Of the projects, 715 were set up in free zones with a
capital of 6.839 billion pounds (2.01 dollars), creating 76,354
jobs.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia tops the list with shares in 345 projects whose
capital is estimated at 2.13 billion dollars or nearly one third
of the Arab investment, it noted.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait takes the second place with shares in 116 projects with
1.25 billion dollars, or 18 percent of the Arab capital. It was
followed by Libya, which has shares in 90 projects.
</P>
<P>
The United Arab Emirates keeps shares in 73 projects, Bahrain
in 30, Jordan in 121, Lebanon in 115, Qatar in 20, Syria in 104,
Palestine in 90, Sudan in 52, Iraq in 41, Yemen in 29, Oman in 14,
Algeria in four and Tunisia in 10. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
