<HEADLINE> Job-Guarantee Deal Sealed at Mercedes-Benz </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, February 28 (Xinhua) -- Amid waves of job cuts in a
sluggish German economy, the management and labor organization of
the German luxury carmaker Mercedes-Benz reached a deal today to
guarantee the 134,000 company workers' jobs in Germany through the
year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Under the accord, which both sides hailed as an effort to cut
costs and assure the company's competitiveness, employees signaled
a readiness to accept restrictions on their future wage increases
as a tradeoff for the job guarantee.
</P>
<P>
The agreement would help to achieve cost savings of 250 million
Deutsche marks (148 million U.S. dollars) in the truck
manufacturing division which currently is operating in the red,
company sources said.
</P>
<P>
The deal could be received as good news for the German economy,
which is plagued by a record high unemployment of nearly 4.7
million in January, the highest since 1933.
</P>
<P>
"The workers council and company management have done more for
Germany as a production site than the federal government, which is
idly watching how unemployment is rising from year to year," Karl
Feuerstein, head of Mercedes' labor organization in Germany, was
quoted by the German news agency DPA as saying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
