<HEADLINE> Hand-Over Ceremony of Ugandan National Stadium </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, February 28 (Xinhua) -- A formal hand-over and
completion ceremony of the Uganda National Stadium, built with
Chinese assistance, was held today at Nambole, eight km from
capital Kampala.
</P>
<P>
During the ceremony, visiting Chinese assistant minister of
foreign trade and economic cooperation, Yang Wensheng, and
Ugandan minister of education and sports Amanya Mushega signed
the hand-over and completion certificates for the stadium on
behalf of their respective governments.
</P>
<P>
Then the Chinese technical team leader of the stadium project
handed over Mushega a ceremonial key to the stadium.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the occasion, Mushega expressed his deep gratitude
to the Chinese government for helping the people of Ugandan in
building such a "modern sports complex of magnificence".
</P>
<P>
Yang Wensheng said the completion of the stadium is a new
achievement of Sino-Uganda friendship and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
He believed that the completion of the stadium will greatly
contribute to the development of sports activities, improvement
of people's health and enrichment of people's cultural life.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed his gratitude toward the concerned
departments of the Ugandan government for providing great support
to Chinese technicians during the construction of the stadium.
</P>
<P>
The stadium project was constructed under an agreement signed
between the two countries in 1987. It includes a stadium with
40,000 seats for spectators and 200 seats for VIPs, a hotel for
120 athletes and another five practising grounds around the
stadium for sportsmen to practise football, basket ball, volley
ball, tennis and track and field sports.
</P>
<P>
The project, worth 36 million U.S. Dollars, was constructed by
the China Zhejiang Corporation for International Economic and
Technical Cooperation and completed on November 30, 1996, three
months ahead of the deadline.
</P>
<P>
Attending the ceremony were some members of the Ugandan
parliament and cabinet, Chinese Ambassador to Uganda Tan Xingju
and hundreds of Ugandans and Chinese.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government delegation of economy and trade, led by
Yang Wensheng, also attended the ceremony. 
