<HEADLINE> Ontario to Lead Canadian Economic Growth in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, February 28 (Xinhua) -- The provinces of Ontario and
Albert will lead the Canadian economic growth this year, a private
think tank said today.
</P>
<P>
Ontario will lead growth with overall gross domestic product
(GDP) reaching 3.8 percent this year and 3.0 percent in 1998, the
Conference Board of Canada said in its Provincial Outlook.
</P>
<P>
The board is predicting that Canada's economy will grow 2.9
percent nationally in 1997.
</P>
<P>
"Low interest rates are paying off, especially in the housing
sector; and the fundamental ingredients for a strong pick-up in
consumer spending are now in place" in Ontario, the board said.
</P>
<P>
The only drag to overall growth in the province will come from
the deep public spending cuts, it noted.
</P>
<P>
Albert's economy will be close second to Ontario in terms of
GDP growth with 3.6 percent growth in 1997 and 2.9 percent in
1998.
</P>
<P>
The Quebec economy will lag the national average, with sluggish
growth of 0.7 percent, while the conclusion of major megaprojects
in Newfoundland and Prince Edward Island will weaken their
economies this year.
</P>
<P>
The projected growth rates for the other provinces are British
Columbia, 2.5 percent; Manitoba, 2.6 percent; Saskatchewan, 2.1
percent; New Brunswick, two percent; and Nova Scotia, 1.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
Nationally, the jobless rate is expected to remain high over
the next two years, as many discouraged workers will re-enter the
labor force, lured by improving job markets, the board said.
</P>
<P>
"Improving government fiscal and external trade balances should
lift the dollar to 0.765 U.S. dollar by the end of 1998," it
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
