<HEADLINE> US Govt Under Attack for Stalling Land Mine Ban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, February 28 (Xinhua) -- Humanitarian groups and
non-governmental organizations from the United States today
slammed the U.S. administration for stalling a proposed
international ban on the production and sales of land mines.
</P>
<P>
At the ongoing International Conference on Mines, the American
group, comprised of 25 experts and NGO members, urged Washington
to join over 50 other countries, including some NATO members and
most African states, in supporting such a ban.
</P>
<P>
However, a U.S. diplomat claimed it should be a "gradual
process" to reduce the production and sales of the mines, adding
that instead of imposing a ban now, the issue should be discussed
within the framework of the U.N. disarmament conference.
</P>
<P>
Michael Mckinley, counselor of the American Embassy in
Mozambique, argued that the Clinton Administration has been
supporting the mine removal campaign by providing 140 million
U.S. Dollars to 15 countries during the last five years.
</P>
<P>
The argument was immediately refuted by delegates who in turn
called for more support from the U.S. government which they
pointed out has been making much huger profits in producing and
selling land mines.
</P>
<P>
"This is really apathetic on the part of the U.S. government
to human sufferings caused by land mines, especially in Africa
and Asia," said an American delegate at the conference.
</P>
<P>
"I regret to see that a big land mine-producer such as the
United States, could not contribute more financial support to
those land mine victims in Africa who are penniless, denied
necessary medical treatment and see no hope of health recovery,"
said Jerry White, director of the Network of Land mine Survivors.
</P>
<P>
The Fourth International Conference on Land mines, attended by
400 delegates from 60 countries and originally scheduled to last
for three days, entered into the fourth day today. 
</P>
</TEXT>
