<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AIDS Deaths Drop Substantially for First Time </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, February 28 (Xinhua) -- For the first time since the
AIDS epidemic began in 1981, the number of deaths from the fatal
disease has dropped substantially across the United States, the
New York Times reported today, quoting Federal health officials.
</P>
<P>
The overall decline was about 12 percent--to 22,000 in the
first six months of 1996 from 24,900 in the same period of 1995--
in all regions of the country.
</P>
<P>
The national decline was less than 30 percent drop reported in
New York City where health officials announced last month that
their figures for all of 1996 showed the first documented drop in
AIDS deaths anywhere in the country.
</P>
<P>
The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention noted in its
weekly report that Deaths from AIDS for women rose 3 percent in
the national data while AIDS deaths of women in New York City
dropped 24.5 percent. But the reasons are unknown.
</P>
<P>
Federal officials attributed the overall drop in deaths in part
to the benefits of combinations of anti-H.I.V. drugs used over
recent years, as well as to better access to care and increased
financing for AIDS treatment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
