<HEADLINE> France, Annan Call for Multinational Force in Zaire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, February 28 (Xinhua) -- France and the United Nations
Secretary General Kofi Annan today relaunched a call for the
deployment of a multinational force in eastern Zaire, after a
genocide against Hutu refugees reportedly took place there.
</P>
<P>
After holding talks today with French Foreign Minister Herve de
Charette, Annan said that he would ask the member states of the
United Nations to study the deployment of a multinational force in
Zaire.
</P>
<P>
"The humanitarian situation (in eastern Zaire) is very grave. I
hope that it will be possible for me to convince the member states
of the United Nations to come to help the refugees and displaced
population in eastern Zaire. There is a great emergency," said
Annan.
</P>
<P>
De Charette said that it appears that there is a big tragedy
going on in that region, and he said that it is "indispensable to
stop the hostilities."
</P>
<P>
He again called for the launching of an investigation into the
reported genocide against Hutu refugees in the rebel-controlled
area of Zaire.
</P>
<P>
French television have shown films shot by amateurs portraying
pictures of massacred refugees, including women and children, in
the eastern part of Zaire.
</P>
<P>
Some children were seen mutilated and laid dead in refugee
camps overrun by unspecified armed groups.
</P>
<P>
A witness's report published in Belgium this week said that
500,000 Rwandan Hutu refugees are missing and some mass graves
were found near the refugee camps of Mugunga and Katale.
</P>
<P>
The report was "categorically" denied by Filippo Grandi, a
representative of the United Nations High Commission for Refugees
in Goma, eastern Zaire, although he said that killings did take
place against refugees.
</P>
<P>
France proposed the deployment of a multinational forces in
Zaire after fighting broke out in eastern Zaire between the
Tutsi-led rebels and Zairean government forces in October last
year.
</P>
<P>
The proposal was reluctantly accepted by the United States in
early November and was voted into a resolution by the United
Nations Security Council on November 15.
</P>
<P>
But it was scrapped by the United States and some other Western
countries after some 600,000 Rwandan refugees suddenly returned
home from Zaire in December. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
