<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Makinen Leads in First Day of Safari Rally </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 1 (Xinhua) -- Reigning world champion Tommi
Makinen overcame punishing conditions on Saturday to take the lead
in Kenya's Safari Rally, round three of the World Rally
Championships.
</P>
<P>
World championship leader Carlos Sainz was forced out midway
through the second stage when he swerved to avoid an animal. He
had been in third place at the end of the first stage.
</P>
<P>
The Spaniard's Ford car plunged off the road and suffered a
puncture. Although he managed to repair it, dust damaged the
wheel nuts, forcing him to withdraw.
</P>
<P>
Makinen, who won the event last season, fought back from a
first stage crash that caused a puncture and left him down in
fourth place in his Mitsubishi.
</P>
<P>
German Armin Schwarz was only 33 seconds behind after more than
220 kilometers of competitive stages through some of the most
difficult terrain faced on the world rally calendar.
</P>
<P>
"The conditions are unbelievable. This year the rally is very,
very dry, but it still makes the conditions incredibly tough and
unpredictable," said Swede Kenneth Eriksson, who was the first
high-profile retirement from the event.
</P>
<P>
The winner of this year's Swedish Rally dropped out at the end
of the first stage after leaving the service area too late
following accident damage repairs.
</P>
<P>
Despite being 50 kilometers from the end of the stage, Eriksson
was able to continue on the run with three wheels on his Subaru,
even reaching speeds of up to 120 kph, but the repairs took too
long at the end of the stage.
</P>
<P>
His Subaru team mate Briton Colin McRae, in fourth place at the
end of the second stage, also encountered difficulties in that
first leg. He suffered two punctures and, with only one spare,
was forced to complete that opening stage with a flat tyre.
</P>
<P>
With two stages left on Saturday, the most obvious threat
remains home favourite Kenyan Ian Duncan, who lies in fifth place
at the end of the second stage and could repeat his victory from
the 1994 rally. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
