<DOCNO> XIE19970301.0073 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Top Advisory Body Contributes to Poverty Reduction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 1 (Xinhua) -- China's top advisory body, the
National Committee of the Chinese People's Political Consultative
Conference (CPPCC), has taken an active part in the country's
endeavor to eliminate poverty.
</P>
<P>
Latest official statistics available show that the population
of the needy in China had dropped to 58 million by the end of 1996
from 250 million in 1978.
</P>
<P>
"The CPPCC National Committee has made a positive contribution
to this historic achievement," said Yang Rudai, vice-chairman of
the CPPCC National Committee.
</P>
<P>
The CPPCC, which is in session here in the Chinese capital, has
attached overriding importance to providing the people in need
with the daily necessities and and helping them to become
better-off, said Yang, who is also president of the China Poverty
Relief Foundation.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, ten of the CPPCC's 25 survey reports were related with
economic and social development in the poor areas, he told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
The proposal of the CPPCC National Committee on accelerating
development of grassland-based animal husbandry was raised
precisely to help herdsmen in grassland areas across China to get
rid of poverty and become better-off, Yang said.
</P>
<P>
He went on to say that the CPPCC National Committee last year
submitted 1,069 proposals concerning economic matters and most of
them were related to central and west China, where herdsmen of
national minorities are relatively concentrated.
</P>
<P>
"Our proposals and opinions have drawn the attention from the
central and local governments and concerned departments," Yang
said, adding that some of these proposals have been accepted by
some policy-making bodies.
</P>
<P>
He pledged that the CPPCC National Committee will go on
submitting motions or bills or suggest ways or means, so as to
contribute to the Chinese government's poverty-relief effort.
China plans to enable another 10 million relatively poor farmers
to have enough to eat and wear this year. "Although China's task
to eliminate poverty is still arduous, I believe the goal will
certainly be achieved by the end of this century," Yang said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
