<DOCNO> XIE19970301.0074 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NPC Deputies Voice Wishes (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Deputy Yang Chuantang, deputy secretary of the CPC Tibet
Autonomous Regional Committee, said, "Today's Tibet has political
stability, ethnic unity, economic development, well-defended
borders and higher living standards for the people. And the
Tibetan people are full of confidence about China's future."
</P>
<P>
Li Youwei, secretary of the CPC Shenzhen Municipal Committee,
has been one of the most sought-after figures whenever the NPC
is in session.
</P>
<P>
Again surrounded by reporters, Li said that Shenzhen has made
remarkable progress in building a socialist market economy in
accordance with Deng Xiaoping's theory of building socialism with
Chinese characteristics, and will continue to pursue reform and
opening policies under the leadership of the CPC Central Committee
with Jiang Zemin at the core.
</P>
<P>
For Economist Zhang Zhongli, it is the 15th NPC session he has
attended. The three-time NPC deputy from the Shanghai Academy of
Social Sciences said he especially felt "the significance of his
responsibility" since this will perhaps be the last NPC session he
will attend.
</P>
<P>
"I have witnessed the NPC playing an increasingly important
role in China's political, economic and social life over the past
15 years," the 76-year-old deputy said.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the wish that the current session and the Ninth
NPC to be elected next year will increase the pace of legislation
and strengthen supervision over law enforcement, to make China a
more prosperous, democratic and civilized nation.
</P>
<P>
In the past 15 years, Zhang has submitted more than 30 bills or
proposals, of which more than one third were enacted as law.
He has again submitted four to the current session,
which concern financial reform, social relief, business operation
system, and international leasing business. 
</P>
</TEXT>
