<DOCNO> XIE19970301.0097 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines, South Africa to Strengthen Trade Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 1 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines and South Africa
today agreed to strengthen their economic and trade ties by giving
each other most favored nation status and establishing a joint
trade committee.
</P>
<P>
A wide-ranging trade agreement to this effect was signed after
a meeting between Philippine President Fidel Ramos and his
visiting South African counterpart Nelson Mandela.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement which is the first between the two
countries, both sides agreed to give each other
most-favored-nation treatment in accordance with the principle
contained in the World Trade Organization Agreement.
</P>
<P>
The two countries also agreed to grant most-favored-nation
treatment to merchant cargo vessels, cargo planes and their crew.
</P>
<P>
A joint trade committee will be established to discuss measures
for the expansion of direct trade between the two countries and
oversee the implementation of the agreement.
</P>
<P>
This agreement, which will come into force soon after gaining
approval from the two countries' parliaments, will be valid for
three years and, thereafter, automatically be extended for another
three years if neither party wants to terminate it.
</P>
<P>
During the one-hour meeting, both Ramos and Mandela pledged to
further boost trade and economic cooperation, which have developed
significantly in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Trade between South Africa and the Philippines reached close to
100 million U.S. dollars in 1996, increasing greatly over the 1991
level of only 4 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Mandela also asked for Philippine assistance in developing
South Africa's electronics industry and promised to send mining
experts to the Philippines to help it develop its mining industry.
</P>
<P>
Mandela, who arrived here this morning on a three-day visit,
today also met with Speaker of the Philippine House of
Representatives Jose de Venecia and Senate President Ernesto
Maceda.
</P>
<P>
After his visit to the Philippines, the first by a South
African head of state, Mandela will leave for Brunei to continue
his five-nation Southeast Asia tour which will also take him to
Indonesia, Malaysia and Singapore.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, business leaders from the two countries will hold a
seminar to seek ways of boosting bilateral trade and economic
cooperation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
