<HEADLINE> Ma Enhua: China's Model Entrepreneur (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 1 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Li Peng listed 10
model workers emerging in recent years, in his government work
report at the opening ceremony of the Fifth Session of the Eighth
National People's Congress.
</P>
<P>
Following is a brief introduction to one of them, Ma Enhua, a
model entrepreneur from north China's Hebei Province.
</P>
<P>
In July 1984, Ma, who had spent most of his life in the textile
industry, was appointed manager of the Baoding Cotton Mill, a
state-owned enterprise on the verge of bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
He tried every means to foster the workers' affection and
enthusiasm for the factory, and gave full play to the workers'
collective wisdom through the introduction of democratic
management.
</P>
<P>
The factory was later turned into the Baoding No.1 Cotton
Textile Group Company, a leading cotton textile enterprise across
the country, of which Ma was director of the board, general
manager, and secretary of the Party committee.
</P>
<P>
Ma, a representative of outstanding managers of large and
medium-sized state enterprises, was reputed as "the socialist
entrepreneur."
</P>
<P>
He was bestowed with the title of "National Model Worker" in
1995, and died of stomach cancer in November of the same year. He
was 58.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
