<DOCNO> XIE19970301.0106 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kong Fansen: A Life's Dedication for Tibet (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 1 (Xinhua) -- Kong Fansen is one of the 10 model
workers commended by Premier Li Peng in his report on the work of
the government delivered at the opening meeting of the Fifth
Session of the Eighth National People's Congress (NPC).
</P>
<P>
Kong, of Han nationality and a household name in China, is
known for his life's dedication to Tibet.
</P>
<P>
He was brn in 1944 of a poor farmer's family in east China's
Shandong Province. He joined the army and, after demobilization,
worked in his hometown before being twice assigned to work in
Tibet.
</P>
<P>
He died on duty in 1994 when he served as secretary of Ngari
Prefecture's Communist Party Committee.
</P>
<P>
He worked tirelessly for Tibetans and won their affection and
respect. Local Tibetans saw him off with tears in their eyes when
he left Tibet after serving his first three-year term.
</P>
<P>
In spite of many difficulties at home -- his mother was too old
and weak to be self-reliant, and his wife suffered from diseases,
a situation requiring him to look after his three children at home
-- he chose to work in Tibet again in 1988, because he was needed
there.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to his leadership, Ngari Prefecture produced 180 million
yuan in gross domestic product in 1994, an increase of 37.5
percent over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Kong died in a car accident on his way to inspect border trade.
Things left by him included 8.6 yuan, his entire monetary
possession, and a letter he wrote four days before his death with
a 12-point proposal on developing the local economy in Ngari area.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
