<HEADLINE> Li Guo'an: "Source of Water" for Inner Mongolians (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 1 (Xinhua) -- Li Guo'an is one of the ten model
workers commended by Chinese premier Li Peng in his government
work report at the opening meeting of the Fifth Session of the
Eighth National People's Congress.
</P>
<P>
Li, a regimental commander serving under the Beijing Military Area
Command, has led troops in digging wells in north China's
Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region for five consecutive years.
</P>
<P>
Local residents, who have had access to drinking water and shed
poverty thanks to Li and his soliders, call Li a "source of
water." In times of peace, the Chinese People's Liberation Army
has the responsibility to help local people develop their economy.
</P>
<P>
Li, 50, has led a water-supply regiment in looking for and
finding water in many desert areas where experts had asserted no
water existed.
</P>
<P>
Tianshuijing, or "Sweet Well," is a new place name added to the
map of China. It is named after a well dug by Li and his men.
</P>
<P>
But Li's health deteriorated in the midst of his strenuous work
and he finally had to recuperate in hospital.
</P>
<P>
He was received by Chinese President Jiang Zemin in 1993, who
highly praised him for carrying forward the fine qualities of the
Chinese Communist Party.  
</P>
</TEXT>
