<HEADLINE> 60,000 Mozambicans Take Refuge in Malawi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, March 1 (Xinhua) -- There are now an estimated
60,000 Mozambicans who are taking refuge in Malawi because of
flood.
</P>
<P>
This was disclosed Friday by the Department of Prevention
and Combat of Natural Calamities (DPCCN) of Mozambique,
according to today's local media.
</P>
<P>
Joao Zamissa who is in charge of DPCCN said that despite the
help provided by DPCCN, these refugees are still in urgent need
of food.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Mozambibique government has instructed
DPCCN to work together with other organizations in Tete and
Zambezia province for creating conditions for the return of the
refugees.
</P>
<P>
Since the Mozambique government appealed to the world for help
to the flooded areas last week, UNICEF has provided medicines in
addition to 10,000 US dollars. Portuguese organization of
cooperation and the European Union have also expressed
willingness to help. 
</P>
