<HEADLINE> Kazakhstan, Japan Sign Loan Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA ATA, March 1 (Xinhua) -- Kazakhstan and Japan have signed
here an agreement, under which Japan will extend a 30-year loan of
21.5 billion yen (about 188 million U.S. dollars) to Kazakhstan.
</P>
<P>
Kazakhstan Pravda, an official newspaper, reported today the
document was signed Friday by Kazakh Foreign Minister Kasymzhomart
Tokayev and Japanese Ambassador Kazakhstan Hidekata Mizouhasi.
</P>
<P>
The financing, earmarked for building a bridge over the Irtysh
River in Semipalatinsk province, was initially agreed on last year
during Kazakh Prime Minister Akezhan Kazhegeldin's tour of Japan.
</P>
<P>
The loan carries a term of 30 years with a grace period of 10
years and an annual interest rate of 2.7 percent, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Besides, Japan will provide another loan of 457 million yen
(400,000 dollars) to help the former Soviet republic rebuild its
famous Medeo mountain skating rink near the capital Alma Ata.
</P>
<P>
Japanese government has offered several loan projects to the
central Asian country for its reconstruction work in recent
years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
