<DOCNO> XIE19970301.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Safari Rally Starts in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 1 (Xinhua) -- The 555 Safari Rally Kenya, the
third round of World Rally Championship (WRC), opened this morning
as Spanish Carlos Sainz first drove his tangerine Ford car out
away from the downtown Nairobi like a flying rainbow.
</P>
<P>
Sainz, the world championship leader, was followed by Subaru
driver Eriksson, winner in the latest round in Sweden, Mitsubishi
driver Tommi Makinen, the 1996 Safari champion, and other 84
entrants, three minutes between each car.
</P>
<P>
When fast-rising local driver Ian Duncan and four-time Kenya
National Rally Champion Patrick Njiru appeared on the platform
from where all drivers start their rally, enthusiastic hail arose
among thousands of viewers in and outside the Kenyatta
International Conference Center.
</P>
<P>
The leading two-car teams also include current European
Champion Armin Schwarz (Ford), 1995 World Champion Colin McRae
(Subaru), and serious contender Richard Burns (Mitsubishi).
</P>
<P>
The route of the first day rally totals will lead drivers to
cover 584 kilometers distance, including 406.10 kilometers of four
competitive sections.
</P>
<P>
Servicing will be solely restricted to designated sites, with
one at the end of every competitive section and just before the
start of the first competitive stage on each of the three days.
</P>
<P>
It was a little cloudy and windy earlier this morning then
powerful sunshine illuminates everything.
</P>
<P>
High temperatures were still expected to bring some
difficulties for the drivers in the rally, held three weeks
earlier this year than ever before, leaving the route extremely
dry and dusty.
</P>
<P>
"Everything would happen," said Sainz, adding however he would
take it easy.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Makinen, nicknamed Flying Finn, said that he thought
things seems to be all right.
</P>
<P>
"I think I have a good chance to win," he said with a bright
smile.
</P>
<P>
After two rounds of the 1997 WRC, Sainz leads the drivers
standing with 12 points. Swedish Eriksson and Italian Piero Liati
have 10 each and Makinen eight.
</P>
<P>
There are 63 cars listed for the main event and 24 for the
parallel Classic classes in the rally, representing a total of 22
motor makers with crews from 19 countries.
</P>
<P>
The 555 Safari will run over 13 competitive sections and 2,400
kilometers of Kenya's spectacular terrain.
</P>
<P>
The annual rally, first held in 1953 to celebrate the
Coronation of British Queen Elizabeth II, was listed as an event
for the World Championship of Makes in 1970. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970301.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-01 </DATE_TIME>
