<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-01 13:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mubarak, Arafat Hold Tete-a-tete Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 1 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
today held talks with Palestinian National Authority President
Yasser Arafat to coordinate steps on the Mideast peace
developments before their upcoming visits to Washington.
</P>
<P>
Arafat arrived here before noon on a brief visit to Egypt,
where he will also address an opening session of the Arab League
emergency meeting on the repercussion of the Israeli new housing
plan in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
A ministerial committee of Israel endorsed an agreement
Wednesday on establishing 6,500 housing units for the Jewish
settlers in Gabal Abu Ghoneim region, known in Israel as Har Homa,
a tree-covered hill taken by Israel in the 1967 Middle East War.
</P>
<P>
The PNA says the envisaged housing project flagrantly violates
relevant U.N. resolutions and the Oslo agreements, signed between
the Palestinians and the Israelis, and stumbles the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Arafat has attacked the envisaged project as a serious breach
of all agreements and regarded it an attempt to cement Israel's
hold over East Jerusalem, which the Palestinians want to have as
the capital of a Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
Advisor to the Palestinian leader Nabil Abu-Rudaina said today
Arafat was keen on consulting Mubarak before heading to Washington
this week to discuss the latest developments in the region and
moves in the near future.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Voice of Arab radio, Abu-Rudaina said
Arafat will discuss during his Washington trip on March 3 the
future of the Mideast peace process in the light of Israel's
decision to build up new Jewish settlements in addition to
Palestinian-U.S. relations, Abu-Rudaina said.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian side will ask the U.S. administration to put
into effect all agreements signed by the parties concerned with
the peace drive, sponsored by Washington, he said.
</P>
<P>
Arafat's Washington trip precedes Mubarak's set for March
10. Jordan's King Hussein is next in line and will be in the
U.S. capital one week after Mubarak. The series of visits followed
the meeting between U.S. President Bill Clinton and Netanyahu in
February.
</P>
<P>
The Mubarak-Clinton meeting is expected to focus on reviving
the stalled talks between Israel and Syria and the opening next
month of Palestinian-Israeli negotiations to determine the final
status of the Occupied Territories.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, Mubarak will meet with Netanyahu on the future of
Mideast peace which is in danger of the deteriorating situations
and increasing complications.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, the first country to make peace with the Jewish state,
in 1979, is a strong advocate of the Palestinian cause and a key
negotiator in the peace talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970301.0116 </DOCNO>
