<HEADLINE> India Wants to Resume Talks with Pakistan Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, March 1 (Xinhua) -- Indian External Affairs Minister
I.K. Gujral said here today that India wanted to resume talks soon
with Pakistan to improve bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
India has taken positive initiatives for speedy progress in
holding talks with Pakistan in a changed global scenario which
calls for greater cooperation among countries, Gujral said while
inaugurating a three-day conference organized by the All India
Peace and Solidarity Organization.
</P>
<P>
There has been tremendous improvement in India's relationship
with the countries of the South Asian Association for Regional
Cooperation (SAARC) consisting of Bangladesh, Bhutan, India, the
Maldives, Nepal, Pakistan and Sri Lanka and things are moving in
the positive direction for establishing friendly ties with
Islamabad too, he further said.
</P>
<P>
Last month as soon as he was elected prime minister of
Pakistan, Nawaz Sharif expressed his country's willingness to
resume talks with India and the Indian prime minister gave his
positive response to Nawaz's appeal.  
