<HEADLINE> Bore Wells Drilling Project Starts In Dar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, March 1 (Xinhua) -- The newly formed Dar es
Salaam Water and Sewerage Authority (DAWASA) had embarked on the
project of drilling 300 bore wells in the city for five weeks,
the project Coordinator, David Songea said here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Mr. Songea from the Ministry of Water noted the 300 wells
being drilled are spread in all the three districts of Dar es
Salaam, and would cost 3779 million Tanzania Shillings (Tsh)
(about 6.3 million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The money constitute the initial funds for phase one drilling
programme.
</P>
<P>
This is part of the government's ambitious and mostly disputed
drilling project set to drill 4,500 wells to alleviate the water
crisis in the city.
</P>
<P>
Songea added that a well drilled in a deep bore costs about 4
million Tshs (about 6,666.6 USD), while the tubes cost 700,000
Tshs with the deep bore generating 72,000 litres an hour.
</P>
<P>
He further said the street water committee would suggest to
the consumers to contribute to the utility of water.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the board of DAWASA chaired by Mr. Nerei
Msimbira with nine other members had the role to educate the
public on water conservation and take legal measures against
defaulters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
