<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: HK To Further Weather Forecast Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 1 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Observatory is
expecting further cooperation with the Guangdong Meteorological
Bureau in weather forecast by jointly setting up their 4th
automatic weather station (AWS) on Dangan Dao, an island to the
south of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Located at the Pearl River Estuary, the AWS will transmit data
on wind direction, wind speed, air temperature, air pressure and
rainfall to the observatory every 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
The data will then be transmitted to Guangzhou through a
network for exchange of meteorological data.
</P>
<P>
Ng Kin Fai, leader of the Electronic Maintenance Team of the
Observatory, said that in this way, valuable meteorological data
are provided to both the Hong Kong and Guangdong meteorological
authorities, facilitating the accurate forecast of hazardous
weather and issue of timely warnings.
</P>
<P>
He said that site selection, communication test and civil work
will start soon and installation work is expected to commence in
the middle of this year.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong and Guangdong began their cooperation in weather
forecast in 1985 when they built an AWS on Huangmaozhou, a remote
island in the south China coastal waters about 50 kilometers
southwest of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
A renovation for the AWS on Huangmaozhou will start soon by the
members of an electric maintenance team of the Hong Kong
Observatory including installing state-of-the-art hardware and
software.
</P>
<P>
Apart from this station, the Hong Kong Observatory and the
Guangdong Meteorological Bureau had jointly established two more
AWSs, one at Tuoning Island to the east and another at Neilingding
Island to the west of Hong Kong. Both were completed in 1996.
</P>
<P>
In the same year, two such AWSs were set up at Sek Kong and Tai
Mo Shan, providing weather watch for the central part of the "New
Territories."
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong is operating one of the most intensive weather watch
networks in the world.
</P>
<P>
Altogether there are more than 60 AWSs in Hong Kong which
transmit data on wind direction, wind speed, air temperature, air
pressure and rainfall to the Hong Kong Observatory every
minute. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
