<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Central Asian States Vow to Save Aral Sea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA ATA, February 28 (Xinhua) -- Heads of state of the five
central Asian nations met here today to step up their rescue
efforts for the world's largest inland lake known as the Aral Sea.
</P>
<P>
The presidents of Kazakhstan, Uzbekistan, Turkmenistan,
Kyrgyzstan and Tajikistan said in the Alma Ata Declaration that
the lake's ecological safety is part of their national security.
</P>
<P>
Some 20 million U.S. dollars have been earmarked since 1993 for
improving the living condition of the people around the devastated
lake bordering the five former Soviet republics, they noted.
</P>
<P>
The Aral Sea's average water level was down by 16.5 meters from
1960 to 1996 as it lost up to 850 cubic kilometers of water.
</P>
<P>
It was the result of a deep reduction of fresh water poured
into the lake from contributory rivers as the former Soviet Union
developed some large-scale irrigation systems at upper reaches.
</P>
<P>
That has led to a sharp increase of salt content in the
remaining water in recent years, and has put plants and animals
there and around on the verge of extinction.
</P>
<P>
In addition, salt that has been deposited on the large areas of
dry lake bed is turned into dust and blown to nearby regions,
seriously damaging the ecological environment there.
</P>
<P>
The calamity of the Aral Sea has been a great concern across
the five newly independent republics, which established in 1993 an
international fund for saving the Aral Sea.
</P>
<P>
During today's meeting, the participants from the five
countries finalized the fund's institutional structure and elected
Uzbekistan President Islam Karimov as its second president after
Kazakhstan President Nursultan Nazarbayev.
</P>
<P>
The heads of states noted that the most urgent task at present
is to extend humanitarian assistances, such as medical services,
drinking water and food, to people living around the lake.
</P>
<P>
They also agreed that the use of water resources in the region
should be coordinated, and that efforts must be made to curb the
fast growing salinization of soil.
</P>
<P>
The Aral Sea protection fund has also won a 380 million dollars
aid from the World Bank, they added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970301.0134 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Police Smash Vehicle Stealing Syndicate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 1 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong police have smashed a
vehicle crime syndicate following the recovery of about 20
suspected stolen vehicles in Yuen Long recently, a police
spokesman said here today.
</P>
<P>
The recovered private cars, most of which are luxury left-hand
drive Benz, could fetch about 15 million HK dollars (1.94 million
US dollars) on the market, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Acting on information, Organized Crime Triad Bureau officers
found about 20 cars were loaded inside six containers in a
container yard in San Tin.
</P>
<P>
The police officers believed the cars were from Japan and are
liaisoning with their Japanese counterparts on the case.
</P>
<P>
A 29-year-old man was arrested on Friday afternoon and he will
be detained for further inquiries, he said.
</P>
<P>
The latest batch of seizure was a result of follow-up
investigations into the smuggling of 54 stolen cars from Japan to
Hong Kong between January 20 and 30, during which five men, aged
from 30 to 47, have been arrested. 
</P>
</TEXT>
