<HEADLINE> South African President to Visit Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, March 1 (Xinhua) -- South African President
Nelson Mandela will make his first state visit to Malaysia for
five days beginning from March 6, it was officially announced here
today.
</P>
<P>
Mandela would be accompanied by his companion Graca Machel, a
30-member official delegation and 85 representatives of South
Africa's private sector, a foreign ministry statement said.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, he will have an audience with the Malaysian
King Tuanku Ja'afar and a delegation meeting with Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad.
</P>
<P>
"The delegation meeting will focus on bilateral, regional and
international issues of common concern," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Mandela is expected to deliver a keynote address at the
Institute of Diplomacy and Foreign Relations on "South Africa and
Malaysia -- A Joint Vision Towards the 21st Century" and another
address at the Second South Africa-Malaysia Business Forum.
</P>
<P>
The president will also deliver a speech at a luncheon hosted
by the National Chamber of Commerce and Industry of Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia is a major trading partner of South Africa in this
region with total trade amounting to 883 million Ringgit (about
353.2 million US dollars) in 1995 with South African exports to
Malaysia almost doubling to 388 million Ringgit (about 155.2
million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Malaysia established diplomatic relations with South Africa in
November 1993 after the dismantling of apartheid and has been
supportive of the national unity government of Mandela.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir made an unofficial stop-over in South Africa in 1992
and his first official visit was in August 1995.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
