<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-01 11:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Census Shows Iran Has 59.5 Million Population </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, March 1 (Xinhua) -- A 1996 national census showed that
Iran's total population stood at 59.5 million, the Persian daily
Salam reported today.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Abbas Ali Zali, head of the Statistical
Center of Iran, as saying that there are 12.4 million families in
Iran.
</P>
<P>
However, the figure seems much less than predictions made by
the United Nations population specialists who claimed that Iran
has about 65 million population.
</P>
<P>
Iranian Minister of Health Ali Reza Marandi said earlier
"There are a large number of children under 16 or 17 who are
reaching gradually the age of marriage. In other words, 25
million youngsters mean 12.5 million couples in the future. If
each couple have two children, still they will add 25 million to
the population."
</P>
<P>
Over the past decade, Iran witnessed a fast growth of
population. Specialists warned that the population would be
doubled again in 20 or 25 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
