<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 1 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading French newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- In the second half of 1996, the number of deaths caused by
HIV lowered by 20 percent in France. In the United States, a
comparable evolution has also been observed. Therapeutic
progresses, such as anti-proteasis and tritherapies, have
contributed to this decrease, the first since the appearance of
the AIDS disease in early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
-- The Pentagon announced Friday that nearly all classified
documents on the using of chemical arms during the Gulf War have
disappeared. The documents include a report on the explosion of an
arsenal of Iraqi chemical weapons, which caused the contamination
of 1,000 American soldiers.
</P>
<P>
-- Russian President Boris Yeltsin Friday asked the Russian
Ministry of Justice to ``prepare for measures'' aimed at
abolishing death penalty. Fifty-two people were executed in
Russia in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- The number of jobless people in France increased by 0.6
percent in January, or 18,600 more people as is compared with
December last year. The unemployment rate of France now stands at
12.7 percent with a legion of 3,099,800 unemployed people, which
represents a 3.1 percent increase over the same month of 1996.
</P>
<P>
-- Belgium remains under a shock after the French auto producer
Renault announced Thursday that it would close a factory in
Vilvoord, Belgium, where 3,100 people are employed.
</P>
<P>
Burdened with heavy deficits since 1995 and threatened with
fierce competition in the European auto market, Renault is
starting a profound restructuring of its industrial sector which
could result in 60,000 more lay-offs in France.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Paris Bourse Friday welcomed the decision by
Renault by pushing up the value of its stocks by 13
percent. 
</P>
