<DOCNO> XIE19970301.0143 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Monthly Review on Manila Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 1 (Xinhua) -- The Manila stock market
consolidated its gains last month after a three-day bull-run
fueled by the country's favorable economic figures for January.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the announcement of the 6.8-percent growth in the
country's gross national product and the 5.5-percent expansion in
the gross domestic product by the government in January propelled
the composite index to a new all-time high on the first trading
day last month.
</P>
<P>
But after the government announced robust economic growth and
strong corporate earnings of publicly listed companies last year,
the market started to correct from its new record of 3,447.60
points on February 6.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the market later consolidated, sending the
composite index (Phisix) down 106.63 points or 3.12 percent to
close at 3,315.28 last month from January's 3,421.91 points. The
all-shares index likewise lost 22.63 points or 1.99 percent to
1,116.46 points from 1,139.09 points.
</P>
<P>
The sub-indices closed mixed. The C-I and property indices
closed down while the mines, oils and financial services ended up.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the volume of shares traded went up by 60.61 percent
to 572.77 billion shares traded last month from January's 356.61
billion shares but value turnover amounted to 72.87 billion pesos
(2.78 billion U.S. dollars) or 4.89 percent less than the previous
month's 76.62 billion pesos (2.92 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
"February was a month of correction as investors opted to take
profits after hitting an all-time high on the first trading day of
the month," DBS Securities Philippines Inc. research manager Jun
Trinidad said.
</P>
<P>
He said the market moved sideways with a downward bias for the
rest of the month. But he pointed out that the market's 3,300
major support level survived the decline as it continued to trade
above the psychological barrier.
</P>
<P>
He said speculative stocks stole the limelight from
fundamentally sound blue chips and second line issues as all 1996
corporate earnings have already been released.
</P>
<P>
Trinidad said attention shifted to speculative stocks due to
the lack of buying incentives for blue chips and second line
issues.
</P>
<P>
"Rumors on possible backdoor listings and corporate takeovers
of dormant and penny stocks dominated the trading last month," he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970301.0144 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-01 10:53 </DATE_TIME>
