<DOCNO> XIE19970301.0145 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lukashenko Calls for More Power to Russia-Belarus Committee </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, February 28 (Xinhua) -- Belarussian President Alexandr
Lukashenko urged today the expansion of the mandate of the
standing executive committee of the Russia-Belarus union to speed
up the integration of the two neighboring states.
</P>
<P>
The committee, currently headed by Russian Prime Minister
Victor Chernomyrdin, should be turned into a supra-national
institution with special jurisdiction, an Interfax news agency
report quoted the president as saying in Minsk.
</P>
<P>
Lukashenko made the remarks after meeting with Russian Minister
for Cooperation with Commonwealth Independent States (CIS)
Countries, Aman Tuleyev, who visited the Belarussian capital to
prepare the two states' Moscow summit on March 7.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the union treaty signed by the two Slav nations
on April 2, 1996, to create a "Community of Sovereign Republics"
with coordinated foreign and military policies failed to build a
mechanism for the implementation of bilateral agreements.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the Belarussian president proposed that the standing
executive committee of the Community be given the mandate to make
decisions with binding forces on the two governments.
</P>
<P>
Under the union treaty, besides foreign and military policies,
the two neighbors will also link their economic and political
systems, and create a common market by the end of 1997 to allow
the free flow of commodities, capital, labor and services.
</P>
<P>
However, Lukashenko said today that it is too early to discuss
whether the Community should be a loose confederation or a close
union, and that the institutional structure is pending the
development of bilateral economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
In his response, Tuleyev said he shared the same view with
President Lukashenko, adding that he had brought along some
proposals for the two states' integration during his visit.
</P>
<P>
If approved and implemented, the Russian minister said, the
proposals will bring down the two countries' energy price index by
half and that of some other commodities by 17 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970301.0146 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Calls for Anti-Fundamentalist Measures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, March 1 (Xinhua) -- Turkey's National Security
Council (NSC) has urged the coalition government to take
measures against "fundamentalist" activities in Turkey.
</P>
<P>
A communique, issued by the NSC following its nine-hour
meeting Friday night, said: "We will not give any concessions
from the contemporary and democratic values of the Republic of
Turkey set up by Ataturk (founder of Turkey)."
</P>
<P>
It added that the nation should not be divided into secular
and anti-secular poles.
</P>
<P>
The NSC meeting, attended by powerful military and civilian
leaders under the chairmanship of President Suleyman Demirel,
discussed the threats directed at the secular Turkey and
intelligence reports which warned that the activities of Muslim
fanatics were aimed at establishing an Islamic state.
</P>
<P>
The Welfare Party's recent proposals on ordering women civil
servants to wear Islamic-style head covering and building a mosque
in one of Istanbul's main commercial squares triggered criticism
from Western-oriented Turks.
</P>
<P>
The Islamic Welfare Party headed by Prime Minister Necmettin
Erbakan came to power last July in a coalition with the secular
True Path Party led by Deputy Prime Minister and Foreign Minister
Tansu Ciller. This is the first time that an Islamic-inspired
party was part of government in Turkey's modern history, which
marked by strict secularism since 1923.
</P>
<P>
Turkey is a Muslim nation but has a secular system and lacks
the religion-based restrictions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970301.0147 </DOCNO>
