<HEADLINE> Ugandan Government Troops Learn Law of War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, March 1 (Xinhua) -- Both junior and senior officers
of Ugandan government troops now are taking their turns in a two
day seminar to learn the law of war, reports from both the north
and the west said today.
</P>
<P>
The seminar is sponsored by the International Committee of the
Red Cross (ICRC) in accordance with the high command of Uganda
People's Defence Forces (UPDF), local English daily "the Monitor"
said.
</P>
<P>
The theme of the seminar is "Basics of Humanitarian Law
Applicable During Conflict". Trainees are also acquainted with
the activities and mandate of the ICRC done on behalf of victims
of war.
</P>
<P>
In northern town of Gulu, such trains were held for 4 turns.
Similar courses are under way now in western Kasese district,
Uganda red cross society reported from the district.
</P>
<P>
Both of the north and the west are rebellion-affected areas in
Uganda.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said there were some indisciplines among
soldiers acting in the western district of Kasese. The high
command of UPDF had ordered to create an office under resident
district councilor in Kasese to deal with the complains from
local residents. 
</P>
