<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Report on Malaysia's CPO, Tin, Rubber Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, March 1 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's markets of crude
palm oil (CPO), tin and rubber closed the week all lower.
</P>
<P>
The CPO physicals were lower with March south dipping by 33.50
Ringgit (about 13.4 US dollars) to close the week at 1,310 Ringgit
(about 524 US dollars) per ton.
</P>
<P>
The CPO physicals are expected to continue to be lower next
week on expectations of higher palm oil production this month.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said February was regarded as a short month for palm
oil production following the long holiday break which slowed down
oil palm fruit harvesting.
</P>
<P>
The weak performance of the market would be also due to the
lack of market direction in the absence of fresh tenders which
prompted players to liquidate their positions, especially towards
the weekend, they said.
</P>
<P>
Cargo surveyor Societe Generale de Surveillance (SGS) on Friday
put Malaysia's palm oil February exports at 453,2 87 tons against
586,046 tons in January, leaving no significant impact on the
market.
</P>
<P>
ON the Kuala Lumpur Tin Market (KLTM), the price closed the
week at 14.25 Ringgit (about 5.7 US dollars) per kg, 39 sen lower
from last week's 14.64 Ringgit (about 5.856 US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Accumulated turnover for the week stood at 514 tons as against
655 tons last week with European, local and Japanese buyers
accounting for the bulk of the transactions.
</P>
<P>
The price differential between the KLTM and that of the LME
stood at a premium of 20 US dollars per ton this Friday against 35
US dollars per ton previously.
</P>
<P>
The tin price on the KLTM might extend its downtrend next week
if the metal's price on the London Metal Exchange (LME) does not
improve, a dealer said.
</P>
<P>
The Malaysian rubber market's sentiment this week was weak as
both buyers and sellers have been sidelined to a wait-and-see
attitude despite some buying interest from China, Australia and
the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
March RSS One closed the week one sen lower to 302.00 sen
(about 120.8 US cents) per kg while SMR 20 added half sen to
296.50 sen (about 118.6 US cents) per kg.
</P>
<P>
The local rubber market is expected to maintain their current
price levels next week following the lack of fresh leads, dealers
said.
</P>
<P>
The steadier Ringgit against the US dollar during the week
under review also dampened market sentiment as most foreign buyers
shifted to other markets like Thailand and Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
The Ringgit stood around the 2.4700 level against the US dollar
early this week from 2.4800 last week.
</P>
<P>
The lack of demand for rubber was also attributed to the fact
that most of the motor vehicle manufacturers have bought enough
rubber for their stocks.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970301.0150 </DOCNO>
