<BODY>
<HEADLINE> At least 200 killed, 1,000 injured in Iranian earthquake </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, March 1 (Xinhua) -- The toll of victims in an
earthquake in northwest Iran rose Saturday to at least 200 people
killed and 1,000 injured, the Islamic Republic News Agency said.
</P>
<P>
The earthquake hit the towns of Ardabil and Meshkinshahr at
4:27 p.m. (1257 GMT) Friday, causing widespread damage in the
surrounding district and toppling houses in some 52 villages, the
news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Emergency rescue teams were rushed to the scene on the edge of
the Talish Mountains some 590 kilometers (365 miles) northwest of
the capital Tehran, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
Iranian TV reported the quake had a 5.5 magnitude. But some
other foreign research agencies reported the quake measuring
magnitude around 6.0 with its epicenter 20 miles (30 kilometers)
west-southwest of Ardabil.
</P>
<P>
Iran is earthquake-prone and is rocked by hundreds of tremors
every year, some of which are deadly and cause widespread damage.
Earlier this month, earthquakes and aftershocks in the northeast
of the country left at least 79 people dead and more than 260
injured.
</P>
<P>
On June 21, 1990, a quake in Iran with a magnitude estimated at
7.3 to 7.7 left 50,000 people dead. 
</P>
</TEXT>
