<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Economy Set for Soft-landing in 1997, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 1 (Xinhua) -- The South Africa's economic
growth in 1997 is expected to slow down but achieve a "soft
landing", setting the scene for higher potential growth in 1998
and beyond, Reserve Bank Governor Chris Stals said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
A local daily The Citizen today quoted the Governor as saying
that the economy would not slide into recession in 1997 but
growth was likely to be "slightly lower" than the 3.1 percent in
1996 and 3.4 percent in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Stals said the structural adjustments were taking place in
economy but "we are heading for what economists will refer to as
a soft landing".
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, most economists in the country are also looking for
growth of two to three percent for the current year.
</P>
<P>
Stals believed that if the key elements of the structural
adjustments, including privatisation, further trade
liberalisation and the gradual removal of exchange controls, went
on smoothly, good growth could be expected for the next three
years.
</P>
<P>
With the Rand slowly regaining its lost ground since the
beginning of the year, the financial stability would be restored
without creating too many hardships so far as real economic
activity was concerned, he added.
</P>
<P>
The Rand, lost about 30 percent of its value in 1996, achieved
quite a good performance in the financial market so far in the
year, reaching a six-month high of 4.457 against the Dollar in
early February. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
