<HEADLINE> Death Toll in Iran's Quake Rises to Some 200 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, March 1 (Xinhua) -- The death toll rose to 200
and 1,000 others were injured in a quake which hit northwest
Iran, the latest report said here today.
</P>
<P>
Iran's official news agency IRNA reported that the earthquake
measuring six degrees on the Richter scale stroke cities of
Ardebil and Meshkin Shahr and their surrounding villages --
about 600 km northwest of Tehran -- Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Some 52 villages south and west of Ardebil have been
damaged by more than 40 percent, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Relief teams continue operations to rescue survivors of the
quake which occurred at 16:31 hours local time (13:01 GMT) .
</P>
<P>
The report said that the tremor, which lasted for about 15
seconds and was followed by Several aftershocks, panicked people
and sent them out into the streets.
</P>
<P>
In the related news, an earthquake measuring 5.5 degrees on
the Richter scale shook the western city of Sanandaj 420 km
northwest of Tehran at 16:28 hours local time (12:58 GMT).
</P>
<P>
However, no report on possible casualties or damage to
properties has yet been received.
</P>
<P>
The tremor measuring about four degrees on the open-ended
Richter scale jolted parts of northern Gilan province at 16:30
hours local time (13:00 GMT).
</P>
<P>
It affected the city of Rasht, Fouman, Shaft, Some'eh-Sara
and part of Khomam, Sangar and Kouchesfahan.
</P>
<P>
This is the second major earthquake within a month. On
February 4, the quake measuring 6.1 degrees on the Richter
scale jolted northern Khorasan province, killing a total of 86
people and injuring hundreds others.
</P>
<P>
Over 100 village suffered varying degrees of destruction,
some totally razed. Over 11,000 houses were damaged, forcing
thousands to become homeless. 
</P>
</TEXT>
