<HEADLINE> Lusaka to Have Better Water Supply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA,March 1 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian capital Lusaka is to
have a better water supply with the completion of phase one of
the Lusaka Water and Sewerage Company (LWSC) infrastructure
rehabilitation project.
</P>
<P>
LWSC supply manager Tenthani Banda told the local press on
Friday that the completed phase includes the refurbishment of
reservoirs, boreholes, pumps, pinelines, a thorough cleaning up
of the database and the installation of a state-of-the-art
computer system.
</P>
<P>
The project was funded with a loan of 40 million U.S. dollars
from the African Development Bank (ADB) and it started in 1989.
</P>
<P>
For years, particularly in 1996, there was water suspension
here and there in Lusaka.
</P>
<P>
"With the ADB and other projects, there has been remarkable
improvements which have satisfied our management. We are quite
sure that by the year 2000, people should be talking about a
different LWSC," Banda said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the ongoing efforts to improve water
reticulation in Lusaka has helped his firm make available 60
percent of the commodity needed in the capital.
</P>
<P>
However, he appealed the Lusaka city council to stop issuing
land indiscriminately without recourse to service provisions like
water supply and sewer systems as his company always finds it
difficult to provide water after plots have been issued and
developed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
