<HEADLINE> CPP Reiterates Position to Boycott NUF </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, March 1 (Xinhua) -- The Cambodian People's Party
(CPP) today reiterated its position to boycott the newly-launched
National United Front (NUF) led by the Funcinpec Party, CPP's
partner in the coalition of the Royal Government.
</P>
<P>
A statement from the spokesman's office of the CPP said, "The
CPP boycotts such a front and this is CPP's common position
already stated by Hun Sen (CPP's Vice-Chairman and Cambodia's
Second Prime Minister) on behalf of the CPP."
</P>
<P>
The statement came in reaction to an interview, carried on
today's local newspaper "Reaksmey Kampucha", which was given by
NUF President Norodom Ranariddh" on NUF's failure to invite CPP to
NUF's founding congress on February 27.
</P>
<P>
Ranariddh, Cambodia's First Prime Minister, was quoted by
the newspaper as explaining that CPP was not invited because he
had heard Hun Sen had declared CPP would not join the Front.
</P>
<P>
Ranariddh was also cited as saying he will choose appropriate
time to meet CPP's Chairman Chea Sim and hand over the NUF's
platform.
</P>
<P>
The CPP statement said the CPP has no need to examine the
political platform of this NUF as the CPP already adopted its own
platform for national reconciliation and development at its
national congress held from January 24 to 27.
</P>
<P>
The statement lashed at the published interview for inciting
split inside the CPP, saying "The CPP considers the above saying
as an action aimed at causing split inside the CPP at a time when
a number of politicians unceasingly provoked the CPP."
</P>
<P>
"It is unique that ruling parties in the coalition ally
themselves with the opposition party that cursed the Royal
Government as one making Cambodia into a mafia state and causing
troubles," the statement said. 
</P>
