<HEADLINE> Students Told Not to Resort to Violent Methods </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 1 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's higher education
minister Ignatius Chombo yesterday said tertiary students should
desist from methods of protest that violate the basis of academic
freedom.
</P>
<P>
He said he believed in academic freedom and there was need to
protect non-violent forms of protest, including demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
"I am opposed to methods of protest, especially the criminal
element that has invaded student protest in recent years and
manifests itself through the destruction of property and the
abuse of ordinary citizens," he said.
</P>
<P>
He was officially opening the first Zimbabwe national students
union three-day congress in Harare.
</P>
<P>
The escalations of demonstrations and strikes at universities
and colleges was not a mere manifestation of the rejection of
parental authority, nor a weakening of state power or immaturity
of students but was reflective of the conflict of generations, he
said.
</P>
<P>
There is therefore need to expose means of minimising the
degree of intolerance in the institutions of higher learning, he
said. 
</P>
