<HEADLINE> Report on Local Autonomy Approved in Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, March 1 (Xinhua) -- The Nepali government has
approved in principle a report on decentralization recommending
for giving more authority to local administrations in the country,
official sources said today.
</P>
<P>
The report was submitted to the government last year by a
high-level decentralization committee formed with the objective of
making local bodies able and efficient under the concept of local
self-governance, according to the Local Development Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Parliamentary bills concerning local bodies on village,
municipality and district level have been drafted on the basis of
the recommendations of the report, the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
Efforts are being made to reach an agreement on these draft
bills through discussions with representatives of major political
parties in the country, it added.
</P>
<P>
It is expected that the government will present the
decentralization bills to the Winter session of parliament which
is to convene from Monday.
</P>
<P>
The forthcoming local elections, which elect chief officers and
representatives for local administration bodies across the
country, will be held after the parliament approves these
decentralization bills.
</P>
<P>
The government last month decided to postpone the local
elections, which were originally scheduled to conclude by
mid-April, till the introduction of the decentralization acts for
more autonomous rights of local bodies.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
