<DOCNO> XIE19970301.0180 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yugoslavia, Bosnian Serb Republic Sign Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, February 28 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslavia and the Bosnian
Serb Republic of Srpska signed an agreement here on Friday to
establish cooperative relations between the two.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was signed by Yugoslav President Zoran Lilic and
the Bosnian Serb member of the Bosnian Presidency, Momcilo
Krajisnik.
</P>
<P>
The Dayton peace accord which ended the three-and-half-year
Bosnian war allows the Bosnian Moslem-Croat Federation to
establish such a special tie with Croatia.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, the two sides will strengthen their
friendship, trust and cooperation on the basis of independence,
equality, respect for human rights and freedom, and
non-interference with each other's internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
The two countries will also make efforts to keep peace and
stability and maintain mutual understanding in the Balkan region.
</P>
<P>
Both Yugoslavia and the Bosnian Serb Republic insisted on
solving the international conflicts and confrontations by peaceful
means. They agreed that neither side would allow its territory to
be used for aggression against the other.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also set up a Cooperation Council, with Lilic and
Krajisnik as its heads, to implement the agreement as well as to
accelerate all-round cooperation in economy, trade, culture,
technology, communications and so on.
</P>
<P>
The agreement will need to be ratified by the Bosnian
parliament before it comes into force. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970301.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Report on Kuala Lumpur Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, March 1 (Xinhua) -- The Kuala Lumpur Stock
Exchange (KLSE) closed the week higher with the Composite Index
(KLCI), the market's barometer, rising 7.81 points to 1,270.67
from last week's 1,262.86.
</P>
<P>
In the week, the all-main board shares Emas Index gained 4.11
points to 374.11 against 370.00 last week.
</P>
<P>
However, the Industrial Index lost 12.88 points to 2,376.92
from 2,389 the previous week and the second board index eased 1.16
points to 649.53.
</P>
<P>
There were 491 gainers, 147 losers and 126 stocks traded
unchanged on the KLSE.
</P>
<P>
Leading the active list this week was Aokam which was up 87 sen
to 5.35 ringgit with turnover amounting to 98.348 million.
</P>
<P>
Suria Capital added four sen to 3.28 ringgit with 94.106
million shares traded, GCE gained 14 sen to 3.54 ringgit with
89.602 million shares traded, KLIH increased eight sen to 4.96
ringgit with 79.495 million shares traded and Insas added 16 sen
to 2.39 ringgit with 78.182 million shares traded.
</P>
<P>
Other active counters included Tekala which gained 95 sen to
7.45 ringgit with 69.050 million shares traded, Econstates added
1.62 ringgit to 5.10 ringgit with 66.783 million shares traded,
but Berjaya Industrial remained unchanged at 3.98 ringgit with
62.491 million shares traded.
</P>
<P>
Consumer products accounted for 298.972 million shares traded,
industrial products 571.059 million, construction 183.897 million,
trading/services 437.003 million, infrastructure 5.341 million,
finance 335.679 million, hotels 181.115 million, properties
717.196 million, plantations 181.764 million, mining 43.155
million, trusts 15.605 million, loan stocks 600.957 million and
call warrants nil.
</P>
<P>
On the main board, turnover increased to 3.179 billion shares
worth 16.879 billion ringgit (about 6.7516 billion U.S. dollars)
from 2.149 billion shares worth 11.168 billion ringgit (about
4.4672 billion dollars) last week.
</P>
<P>
Second board volume this week fell to 220.394 million stocks
worth 2.716 billion ringgit (about 1.0864 billion dollars) from
last week's close at 304.331 million shares valued at 3.799
billion ringgit (about 1.5196 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
Off-market deals shed to 220.332 million shares valued at 1.693
billion ringgit (about 677.2 million dollars) from last week's
245.155 million shares valued at 1.588 billion ringgit (about
635.2 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
Share prices on the KLSE are expected to continue their
consolidation or downtrend phase next week with the CI capping at
between the 1,260 and 1,270 level.
</P>
<P>
Some analysts felt that a strong upsurge in prices may be
dampened redemption by foreign institutions.
</P>
<P>
Others are of the opinion that although the local bourse
recently benefited from "overweighing" by foreign funds, there
were concerns that market might stage another pullback in prices
if foreigners cashed out from their gains.
</P>
<P>
However, most analysts viewed that a correction on the KLSE was
imminent as the CI had climbed substantially over the past few
days.
</P>
<P>
Most also felt that the KLCI's pullback would only be
temporary, given the country's strong economy fundamentals and
improved external trade figures.
</P>
<P>
The Statistics Department reported on Tuesday that Malaysia's
trade deficit shrank to 617.97 million ringgit (about 247.188
million dollars) in 1996 compared with a hefty deficit of 9.36
billion ringgit (about 3.744 billion dollars) in 1995.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970301.0182 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: ASEAN to See Rosier Map of Transport Links </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 1 (Xinhua) -- Southeast Asian nations could
expect a rosier prospect for subregional transport links in the
future as their transport ministers have agreed to push ahead a
Thai proposal to build an ASEAN highway network.
</P>
<P>
Transport ministers of the Association of Southeast Asian
Nations (ASEAN) Friday in northern Thailand agreed to expand the
Thai idea when they hold their next meeting in the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the end of the two-day ASEAN transport ministers'
meeting in Chiang Mai, Thai Transport Minister Suwat Liptapanlop
said that Thailand will go into the details of the project, which
would explore both existing national highways and build new routes
to serve as a link among ASEAN nations and its future members.
</P>
<P>
Measures for forging the highway network, which is designed to
facilitate the flow of goods and people within the region, include
recognizing the driver licenses and vehicle inspection
certificates issued by ASEAN member countries.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, ASEAN now is considering details of a study on a
trans-Asian railway through Indochina and the ASEAN subregion
compiled by the Economic and Social Commission for Asia and the
Pacific (ESCAP).
</P>
<P>
The ESCAP study proposed four possible routes from Singapore to
Kunming city, capital of Yunnan province in southwestern China,
all of which will pass through Kuala Lumpur and Bangkok.
</P>
<P>
Two of the four routes will go through Myanmar, extending 4,794
kilometers and 4,263 kilometers respectively and requiring the
construction of 880 km and 1,293 km of new track.
</P>
<P>
The third will go through Cambodia and Vietnam with a distance
of 5,290 km, within which 288 km of new track will be built.
</P>
<P>
The fourth will run through Laos and cover a distance of 4,105
km with the construction of 1,293 km of new track required.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia also has undertaken to study a trans-Asian rail
network looking at similar routes, which is expected to be
completed in nine months.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia will focus on three components -- economic benefits,
engineering standards and transport facilitation.
</P>
<P>
The economic component includes the number of passengers and
volume of goods.
</P>
<P>
The engineering component will consider rail standards, train
speeds and engineering costs, including the construction of
tunnels and bridges.
</P>
<P>
The third component will focus on the cross-border
transportation of goods and passengers and training of customs and
immigration officers.
</P>
<P>
Malaysian Transport Minister Ling Liong Sik said that Malaysia
will not duplicate existing work and it will collect the results
of other studies.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that the road to integrate the region's road or
rail links is long as more talks are needed to coordinate each
country's positions, but they stressed the process is still
advancing.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970301.0183 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-01 </DATE_TIME>
