<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 76 Dams Built in Myanmar in 9 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, March 1 (Xinhua) -- Altogether 76 dams, including newly
inaugurated Pathi Dam in Bago division, have been built since
1988, official paper the New Light of Myanmar reported today.
</P>
<P>
A total of 405,000 hectares of farm lands were also irrigated
by the dams, the paper added.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the inauguration of Pathi Dam in Toungoo township
of Bago division Friday, Chairman of State Law and Order
Restoration Council Senior General Than Shwe stressed that the
government has given priority to agriculture with huge
expenditures on building irrigation facilities for the development
of agriculture.
</P>
<P>
The senior general urged peasants to boost production and to
respond to the state by being dutiful, and stressed the life of
peasantry will improve two-fold with progress achieved.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar's agriculture, which is the mainstay of the country's
economy, accounts for about 38 percent of the total GDP and about
40 percent of foreign exchange earnings
</P>
<P>
According to the official statistics, Myanmar's paddy output in
the 1995-96 fiscal year was recorded at 19 million tons, while its
rice export was at 353,100 tons. The target for the 1996-97 fiscal
year is to produce 20 million tons of paddy and export 1 million
tons of rice.  
</P>
</TEXT>
