<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Holds Back on Command Changes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, February (Xinhua) -- The North Atlantic treaty
Organization (NATO) has decided that no change will be made to its
command structure until the NATO reform begins, and a balance
between the United States and Europe is attained.
</P>
<P>
The decision will be announced in coming days, a source from
the Italian Foreign Ministry said here today.
</P>
<P>
France suggested in January that the South Command be split
into two, with a European officer in charge of NATO's
ground-stationed forces in southern Europe, and an American
admiral in charge of the U.S. Sixth Fleet and some air and navy
forces in the Mediterranean.
</P>
<P>
But the United States intended to maintain its control over the
South Command, saying it would accept neither a "double command"
for South Command, nor a division of the command into two separate
entities, as had been suggested by France.
</P>
<P>
Instead, it suggested that a NATO "specialized command" be
created for the Mediterranean region under the Naples-based South
Command.
</P>
<P>
The difference between the U.S. and France was put aside by
making no change to NATO's command structure until NATO's reform
began, to avoid turning the structure reform into a dispute
between the U.S. and Europe, said the sources.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970301.0188 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Indian Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, March 1 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Indian newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
The Hindustan Times
</P>
<P>
-- Finance Minister P. Chidambaram Friday evening presented a
