<HEADLINE> Portuguese PM Appeals For Fight Against Drugs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LISBON, February 28 (Xinhua) -- Portuguese Prime Minister
Antonio Guterres appealed strongly today for the whole community
to actively combat drugs so that youngesters can grow up healthily.
</P>
<P>
He made the appeal in the northern city Coimbra, at a signing
ceremony of an agreement between the Post and Communications
Ministry and the Life Project, an anti-drug organization.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, the Ministry will provide the organization
with 50,000 stamps with the words "Revolution Instead of Drugs" on
them, and help it with publicity and educational activities in
schools throughout the country to engender self-protection in
young people.
</P>
<P>
Guterres branded drugs the number one enemy of Portuguese
society. He said the purpose of declaring war against drugs was to
protect the people's lives and health.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that besides the positive and decisive role
business played in the country's economic and modernization drive,
it should also develop a sense of social responsibility to fight
vigorously against drugs.
</P>
<P>
There are more than 100,000 drug users in Portugal at
present. Users are increasing under the age of 15 and above 36,
rising respectively one percent and three percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
