<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka's Tea Output Reaches New Record in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, March 1 (Xinhua) -- Tea production figures in Sri
Lanka last year established a new record of 258.9 million kgs,
registering an increase of 5 percent compared with the figures in
1995, according to the Tea Board sources here today.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that the increase was entirely from the low
grown sector which recorded a substantial increase of 16.3 million
kgs over its previous record whilst production from the high and
medium grown sectors have declined marginally.
</P>
<P>
At present, about 60 percent of this production comes from the
smallholder sector which is a great achievement since 1980's.
</P>
<P>
The sources noted that the Sri Lankan government has taken
several measures to increase productivity and profitability of
tea. Sri Lanka has begun a process of modernizing the tea industry
with the infusion of new capital, new technology and improved
management standards.
</P>
<P>
They added that the private sector with large plantations as
well as the smallholdings plays a dynamic and central role in this
development effort.
</P>
<P>
Tea is one of Sri Lanka's major export items and the source of
26 percent of its export earning. Total tea exports in 1996
recorded 244 million kgs, bettering its pervious record of 240
million kgs in 1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
