<DOCNO> XIE19970301.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Honduras, El Salvador Settle Border Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEGUCIGALPA, February 28 (Xinhua) -- The border crisis between
Honduras and El Salvador has eased following the exit of 16
Salvadoran trucks loaded with timber, and the payment to Honduras
of a 10,000 U.S. dollars fine.
</P>
<P>
The crisis was triggered by an illegal timber operation
performed by Salvadorans living in Nahuaterique and Sabanetas, a
Honduran zone bordering El Salvador.
</P>
<P>
The Honduran Foreign Relations Ministry said today that the
settlement was arranged by the special follow-up commissions made
up of delegates from both countries. On Thursday they went to the
conflict zones of Pasamanos and El Zancudo in the former
Nahuaterique Bolson.
</P>
<P>
The commission will meet again in San Salvador on March 3 and
in Tegucigalpa on March 5 to continue negotiations in a bid to
reach an agreement to solve the problem in a definitive way.
</P>
<P>
Both delegations agreed to promote, through the Honduran Forest
Development Corporation, the implementation of a immediate, just,
and fair solution, taking into account the special circumstances
of the area in the exploitation of forestry resources.
</P>
<P>
They also exhorted the 5,000 Salvadorans living there to abide
by the solutions to be recommended, and to cooperate with Honduran
forest authorities.
</P>
<P>
Honduras and El Salvador staged a "100-hour war" in July of
1969, which was prevented from developing into a serious conflict
by the Organization of American States (OAS).
</P>
<P>
It resulted from an incident with similar characteristics to
the present one: the movement of troops, provocations, and lack
of respect for authorities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970301.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 1996 Good Beginning for Achievement of Trans-Century Goals (37) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 1 (Xinhua) -- A sustained and rapid economic
growth and the effective curbing of inflation highlighted China's
economic development in 1996, indicating a good beginning for the
execution of the country's plan for trans-century goals.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Premier Li Peng made the remark when he delivered his
government work report today at the opening meeting of the ongoing
Fifth Session of the Eighth National People's Congress (NPC), the
Chinese legislature.
</P>
<P>
The premier said that last year's government work report set
forth the target of bringing down the inflation rate from 14.8
percent to about 10 percent in 1996. The actual inflation rate in
1996 dropped to 6.1 percent, remarkably lower than the government's
macro-economic control goal.
</P>
<P>
He added that China's GDP exceeded 6,770 billion yuan in
1996, an increase of 9.7 percent over the previous year as
calculated in terms of comparable prices.
</P>
<P>
The financial situation was stable, and currency issue was kept
under control. And state foreign exchange reserves exceeded 100
billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, China's total grain output amounted to more than 480
billion kg, and its steel output broke the 100-million-ton mark,
according to the premier.
</P>
<P>
Investment in fixed assets came to 2,360 billion yuan, an
increase of 18.2 percent over the 1995 figure, with investment
structure improved and construction of key projects further
strengthened, Li noted.
</P>
<P>
China's central and western regions received more than 43
percent of total state investment in newly-started key capital
construction projects, he said.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, economic restructuring progressed steadily and China
continued to open wider to the outside world, Li said.
</P>
<P>
While lowering the general level of tariffs, the government
modified its policy on import tax reductions and exemptions, and
lowered the rates for tax refunds on exports, he said. And rural
banking reform was initiated throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the government stepped up efforts to reform
state-owned enterprises and experimentation was carried out in
an all-round way, and 58 cities experimented with optimizing
their capital structure, said the premier.
</P>
<P>
He said the ratio of production to marketing and the amounts of
profit and taxes of large enterprises and enterprise groups, a
major concern of the state, rose to some extent; enterprises made
progress in increasing capital and reducing debts; the debt ratio
in some enterprises was lowered; many small enterprises improved
production and operation after they were allowed greater
flexibility.
</P>
<P>
With realization of convertibility of the RMB under current
accounts, the premier observed, China further improved its
investment environment last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970301.0203 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 1996 Good Beginning for Achievement of Trans-Century Goals (38) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In spite of sharp competition on the international market and a
drop in the rate of domestic tax refunds on exports, China's trade
volume exceeded 289 billion US dollars in 1996, representing an
increase of 3.2 percent over the 1995 figure, and a balance
between imports and exports was maintained.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, international tourism brought more than 10 billion US
dollars, while direct foreign investment continued to grow, with
actual investment amounting to over 40 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Talking about new achievements China made in science and
technology, education and other aspects of social development,
Li said that over 2,000 major scientific and technological
advances were officially recognized by the ministries and
commissions concerned.
</P>
<P>
He added that continued efforts were made to expand compulsory
education. By the end of 1996, the goal of nine-year compulsory
education had been accomplished by and large in 50 percent of the
counties (city districts and cities at the county level)
throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
The premier said the living standards of urban and rural people
continued to improve last year. Rural poverty-stricken population
decreased by seven million in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The average per capita income for living expenses reached over
4,300 yuan for city dwellers, an increase of 3.3 percent over 1995
in real terms; while the average per capita net income of rural
residents exceeded 1,900 yuan, an increase of nine percent over
1995 in real terms, the biggest increase in the past few years.
</P>
<P>
The premier said that savings deposits of urban and rural
residents topped 3,850 billion yuan at the end of 1996, an
increase of more than 880 billion yuan from a year before. Urban
employment rose by over seven million people, while new housing
for urban and rural inhabitants totaling 1.1 billion sq m of
floor space was completed.
</P>
<P>
After summarizing last year's achievements, Li pointed out that
there still exist quite a few conflicts and problems in the midst
of economic development, and there are also shortcomings and
defects in the work of the government.
</P>
<P>
He explained that the foundation on which macroeconomic
stability is built is still not solid, and unsound aspects of the
economic structure are apparent. And the agricultural
foundation is still fragile.
</P>
<P>
He went on to say that a certain number of state-owned
enterprises are experiencing difficulties in production and
operation and losses are on the rise. There was an increase in the
number of enterprises which suspended production completely or
partially, causing an increase in unemployment. And corruption and
other undesirable phenomena remain serious problems, he said.
</P>
<P>
The premier called on governments at all levels to do their
utmost to find solutions in days to come.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
