<HEADLINE> NPC Fifth Session Opens  (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
At 9:10 a.m., Premier Li Peng started delivering his report on
the work of the government.
</P>
<P>
He said that 1996 was the first year for implementing the ninth
five-year national plan for economic and social development and
the long-term goals for the year 2010, when new progress was made
in China's reform, opening up and modernization drive, and a good
start was made for the accomplishment of the cross-century
program.
</P>
<P>
He said that in 1997, China will resume the exercise of
sovereignty over Hong Kong and the Communist Party of China will
convene its 15th national congress. These are two events of
far-reaching significance. Guided by Deng Xiaoping's theory of
building socialism with Chinese characteristics and adhering to
the basic line and policies of the CPC, Chinese people should
speed up economic restructuring and a shift in the mode of
economic growth.
</P>
<P>
China should ensure stability and maintain a sustained, rapid
and sound development of its national economy, and promote social
development in an all-round way, the premier said.
</P>
<P>
In his government work report, Li Peng set the rate of economic
growth in 1997 at eight percent. He said efforts should be made to
ensure that inflation in 1997 will be slightly lower than that of
last year.
</P>
<P>
To achieve these objectives, Li stressed that the government
will continue to give priority to agriculture, maintain a
reasonable scale of investment, intensify structural readjustment,
keep carrying out appropriately tight financial and monetary
policies, strive to open wider to the outside world and further
improve the living standards of people in urban and rural areas.
</P>
<P>
Li Peng listed reform of state-owned enterprises as another
priority this year and a pressing task for the government, saying
that greater stride must be made to reform the state-owned
sector.
</P>
<P>
Reform of the state-owned sector takes up more than one sixth
of the government work report, unprecedented in history.
</P>
</TEXT>
