<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Strong Earthquake Shocks Pakistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, March 1 (Xinhua) -- At least 47 people were killed
and about 125 others injured in the earthquake which jolted
central Pakistan early Friday.
</P>
<P>
The earthquake, which measured 6.3 and 7.3 on the Richter scale
and hit Quetta valley and other parts of northern Baluchistan
province at about 2:10 a.m. Friday, was one of the worst in 62
years.
</P>
<P>
According to officials of the Pakistan Meteorological, the
epicenter of the earthquake was 140 kilometers east of
Baluchistan's capital city of Quetta and it was felt in most of
the province and some parts of Sindh province.
</P>
<P>
Emergency was declared in Quetta immediately after the shocks
which lasted for over one minute.
</P>
<P>
Hernai, a sub-division of Sibi division of Baluchistan, is the
worst affected area with 38 people dead and dozens injured.
</P>
<P>
The falling boulders from the mountains after the earthquake
have blocked the Sibi-Hernai road, cutting off Hernai's road links
with other areas.
</P>
<P>
Army troops have been called out in Quetta city to carry out
rescue operations along with the civil administration.
</P>
<P>
Pakistani President Farooq Leghari and Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif Friday expressed their profound grief and shock over the
earthquake.
</P>
<P>
They asked the federal and provincial governments to take all
possible relief measures and provided urgent medical aid to the
victims.
</P>
<P>
Rescue operations are still going on.
</P>
<P>
Loss of lives and damage to property could be much more as some
of the affected areas are inaccessible.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
