<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic News Briefs (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, February 28 (Xinhua) -- The following are the
major economic news briefs from Latin American countries in the
past few days:
</P>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA -- Colombia's state oil firm Ecopetrol's oil
and gas reserves can guarantee the hydrocarbons supply to the
country for at least 50 more years, studies commissioned by the
company said.
</P>
<P>
The studies estimated the reserves at above three billion
barrels of crude oil and 125 trillion cubic feet of gas.
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- Uruguayan exports of meats, sausages, offal, and
meat byproducts rose 23.5 percent from January 1 to February 16,
compared with the same 1996 period.
</P>
<P>
Sales went from 23,737 tons to 29,296 tons.
</P>
<P>
Income for that period increased 17.3 percent to 53.8 million
U.S. dollars, from 46.074 million dollars in the same 1996 period.
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- Foreign investment in Chile reached 620 million
dollars in January, double the amount registered for the same
month in 1996, figures from the Central Bank show.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investment in the country was 6.419 billion dollars in
1996.
</P>
<P>
MANAGUA -- Nicaragua will export 91,000 metric tons of bananas
this year, earning it 25 million dollars in hard currency,
according to Maria Isabel Arguello, president of the board of the
Nicaraguan Banana Producers Association.
</P>
<P>
About 80,000 metric tons, or 90 percent of the exports, will be
sold in the European market, mainly in Germany, and the rest in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- Argentina-Brazil trade will post a new record
this year, with an increase of 20 percent over 1996, said
Brazilian Ambassador to Argentina Castrioto de Azambuja.
</P>
<P>
Argentine Economy Ministry statistics show that the volume of
bilateral trade in 1997 will reach 14.8 billion dollars, with
Argentina enjoying a surplus of more than 1 billion dollars.
</P>
