<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Reduce Illiteracy by Four Million (18) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 1 (Xinhua) -- China will reduce illiteracy by
four million among the young and middle-aged in 1997, Li Peng,
premier of the State Council, said here today.
</P>
<P>
In his government work report delivered at the Fifth Session of
the Eighth National People's Congress (NPC), which opened this
morning, Li said the Chinese government will continue to lay
stress on elementary education, devote major efforts to expanding
nine-year compulsory education and enhance literacy work.
</P>
<P>
According to the premier, half of all counties (city districts
and cities at the county level) throughout the country had
basically popularized nine-year compulsory education by the end of
1996.
</P>
<P>
The NPC in 1986 enacted Compulsory Education Law, which
provides that nine-year compulsory education be basically
popularized and illiteracy basically eliminated throughout the
country at the end of the century.
</P>
<P>
Li said China also recorded gratifying progress in vocational
education. Students in vocational schools account for 56.8 percent
of those eligible for senior secondary school education and the
number of vocational training institutions came to more than
400,000. New strides were made in the reform of the higher
education management system, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
