<HEADLINE> Li Peng on Crime Crackdown (21) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 1 (Xinhua) -- Premier Li Peng said in Beijing
today that China will continue its current crackdown on crimes,
which has lasted nearly a year, to achieve the further improvement
of the social security.
</P>
<P>
In his government work report to the Fifth Session of the
Eighth National People's Congress, which started here today, Li
said that the comprehensive control of public security is an
important issue that must be seriously dealt with.
</P>
<P>
"The past year has witnessed fairly good results in the
large-scale struggle to severely crack down on criminal
activities. The current situation in public security, however, is
not so gratifying," he said, adding that the central government
would continue to take effective measures to concentrate on
combating violent crimes, drug-related crimes, hoodlums and
underground gangsters.
</P>
<P>
He said that the government would resolutely wipe out social
evils, such as pornography, gambling, and drug abuse and
trafficking, and punish those who organize, operate or protect
prostitution activities and the production or peddling of
pornography.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, he noted, there has been a rising trend in the
number of cases of economic crimes, which should be guarded
against and severely cracked down upon.
</P>
<P>
"We should also punish according to law such crimes as
smuggling, manufacture and distribution of fake or shoddy
products, financial swindling and other crimes," he said.
</P>
<P>
He went on to point out that it is necessary to analyse the new
situations and problems encountered in public security work,
correctly handle contradictions among the people, and mediate
various kinds of civil disputes and disputes on economic matters
according to law, so as to eliminate factors contributing to
social instability.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he stressed that personnel in the procuratorial,
judicial and public security departments must improve their
competence politically and professionally, observe discipline,
handle matters impartially, and strictly enforce the law.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
