<DOCNO> XIE19970301.0238 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Continue Fight against Corruption (22) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 1 (Xinhua) -- China will make greater endeavors
to combat corruption and to keep government employees honest and
industrious, Chinese Premier Li Peng said here today.
</P>
<P>
In the government work report he delivered to the Fifth Session
of the Eighth National People's Congress, Li said that leading
cadres should take the lead in strictly following the relevant
regulations requiring them to perform their duties honestly, to be
self-disciplined and to conscientiously subject themselves to
supervision and examination.
</P>
<P>
He demanded that public servants should foster the concept of
serving the people whole-heartedly and raise their ideological and
political level and their professional competence.
</P>
<P>
"They should plunge deeply into the realities of life, do
investigative work, work diligently, improve their efficiency,
avoid a bureaucratic work style and become public servants with
whom the people will be satisfied," said the premier.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that more efforts should be made to handle criminal
cases, and major ones in particular.
</P>
<P>
He added, "we should concentrate on investigating and
prosecuting leading organs, law enforcement departments, economic
management departments and leading cadres at and above the county
(section chief) level that violate the law or discipline.
</P>
<P>
"We should seriously handle cases involving leaders in
state-owned enterprises who squander and embezzle state property
as well as cases involving legal persons who violate laws and
discipline or grossly misappropriate state assets. Those who abuse
their power for personal gain, commit bribery or accept bribes
must, without fail and regardless of rank, be punished according
to law."
</P>
<P>
The premier voiced the government's determination to handle
harshly with malpractice in government departments, trades and
professions, which are particularly repugnant to the people, and
to achieve fresh results in this regard.
</P>
<P>
"Efforts should be made to strengthen supervision over law
enforcement, and we should prosecute those who seriously neglect
their duties," said the premier.  
</P>
</TEXT>
