<DOCNO> XIE19970301.0241 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombian Coffee Still Over 2-Dollar Line </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, February 28 (Xinhua) -- Colombian coffee
continued its "mini-boom" Thursday when it passed the two-dollar
mark on the New York Stock Exchange, to be quoted at 2.02 dollars
a pound.
</P>
<P>
The domestic price of a 125 kilo load last Friday increased to
310,230 pesos (a little more than 310 U.S. dollars), and another
considerable rise is expected today, after the good results
obtained in the market in the past few days.
</P>
<P>
The last time the Colombian bean was quoted above the
two-dollar mark on the international market was November 10,
1994. Then the prices presented considerable recoveries following
a cold spell in Brazil.
</P>
<P>
International quotations during the first two months of 1997
show that a rapid recovery started January 15.
</P>
<P>
Coffee market analysts consider this price rise is due to a
supply shortage among several of the main suppliers.
</P>
<P>
Colombia has faced serious difficulties since last January
because of a labor conflict in the port of Buenaventura, which
developed into a labor stoppage until February 23.
</P>
<P>
New York Stock Exchange operators were alarmed by the stoppage
of state workers in the second week of February, and prices rose
again.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, the market has been influenced by a supply
reduction by Central American countries, as well as by the drop in
the coffee harvest of Brazil, the first producer of the grain in
the world.
</P>
<P>
It has been observed too that the announcement made by coffee
producing countries about reducing the world offer supply by 1.3
million 60-kilo-bags for this half year, was reflected in a
reaction to the rise in the prices of the grain of coffee.
</P>
<P>
The National Coffee Growers Committee (CNC) decided to increase
by 12 percent the domestic price for the 125 kilo load, compared
to what had been in force since the first week of December. With
that the internal price rose from 221,000 pesos to 248,125 pesos
and the internal price was readjusted at 16.87 percent when it
passed from 248,125 pesos to 290,000 pesos. On that occasion the
CNC announced that starting Friday 21 the weekly automatic
fixation system would start to operate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
