<DOCNO> XIE19970301.0242 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Premier on National Economy (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 1 (Xinhua) -- A sustained and rapid economic
development and the effective curbing of inflation highlighted the
performance of the Chinese economy in 1996, Chinese Premier Li
Peng told legislators here today.
</P>
<P>
Li made the assessment when delivering his government work
report at the opening meeting of the Fifth Session of the Eighth
National People's Congress (NPC).
</P>
<P>
China's inflation rate, which reached 14.8 percent in 1995,
dropped to 6.1 percent last year, four percentage points lower
than the initial target, he said.
</P>
<P>
The premier said that price hikes had been a major problem for
the Chinese economy for years, and the falling inflation rate last
year showed that the government has improved the environment for
economic performance as a whole, safeguarded the interests of
consumers and created conditions conducive to lowering interest
rates, reducing production costs for enterprises and decreasing
financial subsidies by the state.
</P>
<P>
However, he pointed out, the government should by no means
relax control over price rises, as pressure from inflation still
exists. To rationalize prices is a long-term task which requires
both a positive attitude and a reliable approach, he said.
</P>
<P>
"We should rigorously limit the number and range of items
subject to this year's price readjustments and set objectives by
taking into consideration the financial capability of all sectors
of the society so as to avoid significant untoward repercussions,"
Li said.
</P>
<P>
He said the government will continue to implement the
responsibility system to attain objectives in price readjustment
and control, and further tighten supervision over and control of
market prices.
</P>
</TEXT>
