<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NPC Fifth Session Opens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 1 (Xinhua) -- The Eighth National People's
Congress (NPC), the supreme organ of power in China, started
convening its fifth general session, the last during its term of
office, in Beijing today.
</P>
<P>
Close to 3,000 deputies to the NPC from across the country
gathered in the Great Hall of the People to hear a report on the
work of the government by Premier Li Peng of the State
Council, China's cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Party and state leaders Jiang Zemin, Li Peng, Qiao Shi, Li
Ruihuan, Zhu Rongji, Liu Huaqing, Hu Jintao and Rong Yiren
attended today's opening meeting and were seated at the rostrum.
</P>
<P>
Qiao Shi, executive chairman of the current NPC
session and chairman of the NPC Standing Committee, opened the
session at 9:00 a.m. The national anthem was then played.
</P>
<P>
Following the ceremony, Qiao said that on the eve of the
session, China's respected and beloved Deng Xiaoping passed away
unfortunately.
</P>
<P>
The passing away of Deng Xiaoping has been an immeasurable loss
to the Party, the army and people of all ethnic groups, Qiao said.
He called for all the NPC deputies to turn grief into strength,
carry work forward at the behest of Deng Xiaoping and unite
closely around the Chinese Communist Party Central Committee with
Jiang Zemin at the core, hold high the banner of Deng Xiaoping's
theory on building socialism with Chinese characteristics, and
adhere to the Party's basic line, in order to advance steadily the
great undertakings of socialist reform, opening up and
modernization drive pioneered by Deng.
</P>
<P>
At the request of Qiao, all present stood up in silent mourning
for Deng Xiaoping.
</P>
<P>
More than 1,800 members of the National Committee of the
Chinese people's Political Consultative Conference and those in
charge of party, government and military organizations were
present at today's opening meeting in a non-deputy capacity.
</P>
<P>
More than 1,000 journalists from domestic and overseas media
covered the meeting. The opening meeting was broadcast or
televised live by the Central People's Radio Station, the China
Central Television Station and China Radio International.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970301.0245 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Premier on National Economy (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China's GDP exceeded 6,770 billion yuan in 1996, according to
the premier, an increase of 9.7 percent over the previous year as
calculated in terms of comparable prices.
</P>
<P>
He noted that government revenue increased considerably last
year, with local revenue exceeding expenditures and central
deficits kept within budgetary targets. The financial situation
was stable, and currency issue was kept under control. State
foreign exchange reserves exceeded 100 billion US dollars and the
exchange rate for the RMB remained stable.
</P>
<P>
Reporting on agriculture, Premier Li told the deputies that
total grain output amounted to more than 480 billion kilograms.
</P>
<P>
By tapping the potential and upgrading technology, Li told the
deputies, the iron and steel industry improved its product mix,
and the steel output topped 100 million tons.
</P>
<P>
Investment in fixed assets came to 2,360 billion yuan, an
increase of 18.2 percent over the 1995 figure, and the investment
structure was improved, said Li.
</P>
<P>
He said that construction of key projects was further
strengthened. Investment in the central and western parts of the
country accounted for over 43 percent of total state investment in
incipient key projects.
</P>
<P>
Citing progress made in the construction of key national
projects, Li said that the Beijing-Kowloon Railway running through
north and south China was put into operation; expressways with a
total length of more than 1,100 km were completed and opened to
traffic; more than 15 million kw of power-generating capacity was
added and the number of telephone lines increased by over 20 million;
the Nanning-Kunming Railway will soon be completed; and
construction of the third-phase expansion project of the Baoshan
Iron and Steel Company and other important projects was
progressing smoothly.
</P>
<P>
These projects will play an important role in readjusting the
industrial structure, promoting coordinated regional development
and increasing staying power for continued national economic
development, the premier said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970301.0246 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Li Peng on Reform and Opening Up  (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 1 (Xinhua) -- Premier Li Peng said today in
Beijing that in 1996 economic restructuring progressed steadily in
China, and that the country continued to open wider to the outside
world.
</P>
<P>
Li made these remarks in a report on the work of the government
he delivered at the Fifth Session of the Eighth National People's
Congress, which opened here today.
</P>
<P>
He said that last year China continued to deepen the reform of
the foreign trade system and the foreign exchange management
system, implemented the proxy system step by step, and gave more
productive enterprises the power to engage in export
independently.
</P>
<P>
"We also realized the convertibility of the RMB under current
accounts and further improved our investment environment," he
said.
</P>
<P>
While lowering the general level of tariffs, he noted, the
Chinese government modified its policy on import tax reductions
and exemptions, and lowered rates for tax refunds on export goods.
</P>
<P>
He said that, despite sharp competition on the international
market and a drop in the rate of domestic tax refunds for export
goods, China's total volume of imports and exports exceeded 289
billion US dollars, an increase of 3.2 per cent over the 1995
figure, and a basic balance between imports and exports was
maintained.
</P>
<P>
"International tourism brought in more than 10 billion US
dollars, and direct foreign investment continued to grow, with
actual investment amounting to over 40 billion US dollars," he
said, adding that more investment was channelled into
infrastructural facilities, basic industries and projects in the
central and western parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
He also pointed out that in 1996 the government stepped up
efforts to reform state-owned enterprises and carried out
experiments on the optimization of the capital structure in 58
cities across the country.
</P>
<P>
"We also accelerated merger and bankruptcy procedures for
enterprises and the dispersion of redundant employees, and stepped
up efforts to rid enterprises of social service functions. The
rates of production and marketing and the amounts of profit and
taxes of large enterprises and enterprise groups rose to some
extent. Enterprises made progress in increasing capital and
reducing debts, with the debt ratio in some enterprises lowered,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Talking about reform of the circulation system, he said that
the state encouraged the development of various modes of operation
and marketing, thus dovetailing production with marketing and
promoting the sale of commodities.
</P>
<P>
"Meanwhile, we raised grain purchase prices. The grain reserves
of the state, local authorities and farmers increased
considerably, which will play an important role in making up for
shortages caused by crop failures and in guaranteeing a stable
supply of grain in the future," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
