<DOCNO> XIE19970301.0247 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Premier Highlights Agriculture (4) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 1 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Li Peng said here
today that China will continue to give priority to strengthening
agriculture in its economic work despite an all-round development
in the rural economy last year.
</P>
<P>
In his government work report to the Fifth Session of the
Eighth National People's Congress, Li said China will continue to
pay keen attention to agriculture and to the construction of water
conservancy projects.
</P>
<P>
"We can never neglect agricultural production, as our country
has a large population but limited arable land and frequently
suffers natural calamities," Li said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the acreage for growing grain and cotton must be
stabilized, adding that China must take precautions against
droughts and floods, prevent grain production from decreasing and
keep up a steady increase in cotton, oil-bearing crops, sugar
crops, meat and aquatic products, so as to promote the all-round
development of farming, forestry, animal husbandry, sideline
production and fishery and increase farmers' incomes.
</P>
<P>
China should maintain and improve the household responsibility
contract system with remuneration linked to output as well as the
two-tier operation system that combines unified management with
independent management, the premier noted.
</P>
<P>
He told the session that the grain circulation system should be
further reformed and the protective pricing system further
improved with a view to encouraging farmers to produce.
</P>
<P>
"We should do a good job in the manufacture and supply of the
means of agricultural production and stabilize their prices," Li
said, adding that China should persist in implementing the system
of provincial governors assuming responsibility for the "rice bag"
and city mayors assuming responsibility for the "market basket".
</P>
<P>
He urged all local governments to earnestly carry out the basic
farmland protection system and to try by every means to use as
little land as possible and strictly control non-agricultural use
of farmland.
</P>
<P>
He said that it is an urgent task for China to strengthen the
construction of water conservancy facilities.
</P>
<P>
"There have been quite severe droughts and floods over the past
few years, " Li said. "Therefore, we should be determined to do
well in water conservancy construction."
</P>
<P>
China shall establish central and local water conservancy
construction funds to increase input in this field, he said.
</P>
<P>
The system of divided responsibility should continue to be
implemented with the state mainly in charge of the treatment of
the main streams of big rivers, local governments in charge of
medium-sized and small rivers and lakes, and municipal governments
in charge of flood prevention in cities, he said.
</P>
<P>
In rural areas, farmers should be organized to involve
themselves in farmland improvement and water conservancy projects
as well as improvement of small drainage areas, the premier added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970301.0248 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rural Poverty-Ridden Population Down Seven Million (5) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 1 (Xinhua) -- China's anti-poverty program,
aimed at meeting people's basic need for food and clothing, scored
a major success last year as seven million poor rural residents
bid farewell to absolute poverty, Chinese Premier Li Peng said
here today.
</P>
<P>
The latest reduction brought China's rural poverty-stricken
population down to 58 million by the end of last year. In 1978,
250 million rural Chinese were living in destitution.
</P>
<P>
The average per capita net income of rural residents last year
exceeded 1,900 yuan, an increase of nine percent over 1995 in real
terms, the biggest increase in the last few years, Li said at the
Fifth Session of the Eighth National People's Congress, which
opened today.
</P>
<P>
He said that it is the government's important duty to relieve
poverty in the countryside and provide poverty-ridden rural
residents with necessary help.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government's financial allocations for poverty
relief and for development in rural areas will increase
considerably this year, Li promised, urging local governments to
increase their part of financial input.
</P>
<P>
"All the funds must be allocated to their designated places on
time and in full and be used for the benefit of poor villages and
poor farmers," the premier urged.
</P>
<P>
The country's ongoing anti-poverty program aims to let all
poverty-ridden rural Chinese have enough to eat and wear by the
end of this century. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970301.0249 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Li Peng on Investment Scale, Structural Readjustment (7) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 1 (Xinhua) -- China will maintain a reasonable
scale of investment, pool more funds for major projects and
intensify structural readjustment so as to avoid duplicated
construction.
</P>
<P>
The remark was made by Premier Li Peng at the Fifth Session of
Eighth National People's Congress (NPC), which opened here today.
</P>
<P>
Li said China will give all-round consideration to the need to
accelerate economic growth and to the feasibility in terms of
financial and material resources.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, China will pour a total investment of 2,530 billion
yuan in fixed assets at an investment rate of 32 per cent. The
investment, he said, will continue to favor agriculture and water
conservancy projects, to favor infrastructural facilities, basic
industries and pillar industries which receive major support from
the state, to favour the central and western parts of the country,
to favour technological upgrading, and to favour the fields of
science, technology and education.
</P>
<P>
According to the Chinese premier, more funds will be pooled for
key projects in order to ensure the completion of these projects
and the commencement of production. A number of major state
projects essential to the restructuring of the economy and a
number of projects which are of great importance for optimizing
the industrial structure and improving regional distribution will
be launched.
</P>
<P>
The year 1997 will witness the damming of both the Three Gorges
and Xiaolangdi projects. In his government work report, Li called
for meticulous care in organizing the construction work of the two
projects and properly handle the issues of resettlement in the
dams areas.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the Chinese government will also speed
up the construction of ordinary housing, which is not only
urgently demanded by urban residents, but also may help boost the
development of related industries, thus nurturing new areas for
economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Li Peng urged localities to conscientiously implement
the policy of shifting the mode of economic growth, strictly
control the launching of ordinary projects in the processing
industry, and avoid "large and all-inclusive" or "small and
all-inclusive" projects as well as duplicated construction.
</P>
</TEXT>
