<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines to Increase Financing to Small Firms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 1 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine Department of Trade
and Industry has planned to increase government financial loans to
the country's small- and medium-scale enterprises (SMEs) by 50
percent to 150 billion pesos (5.7 billion U.S. dollars) in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Citing a report issued by the department, today's newspaper
Malaya said the extra financing will create 550,000 more jobs
across the country.
</P>
<P>
With the new loans, the number of the SMEs will rise to about
280,000 and more local firms will be attracted into the country's
regional growth centers.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the banking system released a total of 100 billion
pesos (3.8 billion dollars) to the SMEs, a 25 percent increase
from 80 billion pesos (3.1 billion dollars) in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Last year's financing assistance represented 13.9 percent of
total loan portfolio of 722.7 billion pesos (27.6 billion dollars)
reported by the country's 563 banks.
</P>
<P>
This rate is 3.9 percentage points higher than the 10-percent
mandatory allocation from banks to lend small enterprises under a
law for SMEs.  
</P>
</TEXT>
