<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Premier Commits to Tight Fiscal, Monetary Policies (9) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 1 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Li Peng said here
today that China this year will continue to follow appropriately
tight fiscal and monetary policies to rein in price rises.
</P>
<P>
The state, especially the Central Government, is still
experiencing financial difficulties, Li told the Fifth Session of
the Eighth National People's Congress, which opened in the Great
Hall of the People today.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, on the one hand, China must improve its taxation
system by levying taxes fairly and tightening tax collection and
management, he said.
</P>
<P>
"We must collect taxes in strict accordance with the law, plug
loopholes such as tax evasion and tax fraud, making sure that all
that is taxable is actually taxed," he said.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, China must strictly control expenditures to
ensure that expenditure increases do not exceed revenues.
</P>
<P>
In preparing their budgets, governments at all levels should
make sure that they can make both ends meet and that budgeted
expenditures cover both material and construction costs, the
premier said, urging local governments to maintain a balance
between revenue and expenditure.
</P>
<P>
China should maintain a measured increase in the money supply,
Li said.
</P>
<P>
"To improve benefits from loans and to support production and
construction, we must restructure loans in accordance with the
state industrial policies, regional policies, policies for
technological development and the rules for granting loans," he
said.
</P>
<P>
He also called state banks to reduce costs and increase
economic returns and said that effort will be made to standardize
the securities and futures markets and heighten people's awareness
of the financial risks therein.
</P>
<P>
On prices, the premier said: "We should by no means relax
control over price rises, as pressure from inflation still
exists."
</P>
<P>
He also highlighted the urgency to reinforce financial and
economic discipline and standardize procedures relating to
financial revenue and expenditures.
</P>
<P>
Financial management of enterprises should be strengthened and
efforts be made to gradually usher in professional auditing
services and strengthen supervision over auditing," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We must resolutely investigate into and punish all kinds of
acts of random and illegal fee-collecting and illegal monetary
apportionment and fund-raising," the premier said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
