<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Li Peng on  Policy of Opening to outside World (10) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 1 (Xinhua) -- Li Peng, premier of the State
Council, said China will open wider to the outside world.
</P>
<P>
In his government work report delivered at the Fifth Session of
the Eighth National People's Congress (NPC), which opened here
today, Li said China will continue to encourage the special
economic zones, the Pudong New Area of Shanghai and other open
areas to play a more prominent role in reform, opening up and
economic development throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
China will make better use of both domestic and international
markets and resources in order to promote continued growth in
foreign trade and maintain a basic balance between import and
export, he said.
</P>
<P>
While consolidating and enlarging existing markets, China will
strive to open new markets and encourage the export of products of
high added value, especially complete sets of machinery and
electrical equipment, he said.
</P>
<P>
More productive enterprises will be entitled to export
commodities on their own, and the system of export tax refunds
will be improved; the proxy system in foreign trade will be
improved; and efforts will be made to make the "Visit China '97" a
big success, he said.
</P>
<P>
Li said China will continue to use foreign funds actively,
rationally and effectively, and encourage foreign businesses to
invest in a comprehensive development of agriculture,
infrastructural facilities, a comprehensive utilization of
resources, industries using high and new technologies as well as
in the central and western parts of China.
</P>
<P>
Efforts will be made to draw on methods compatible with
international standards to keep domestic market competition in
good order. The government will improve services for, and
strengthen administration and supervision of, foreign-funded
enterprises with an emphasis on tax collection and management,
fulfillment of contracts and protection of workers' rights and
interests, he said.
</P>
<P>
"China will unswervingly pursue the policy of opening to the
outside world and will further strengthen its trade and economic
relations with other countries on the basis of equality and mutual
benefit. China's entry into the World Trade Organization accords
with the needs of both China and the world. We shall continue our
negotiations with relevant countries in accordance with the
principle of balanced rights and obligations," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
