<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing's First Wholesale Center for Electronic Publications Opens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 1 (Xinhua) -- Beijing's first wholesale center
for electronic publications and software products opened in
Zhongguancun, China's "Silicon Valley" Friday.
</P>
<P>
The opening of the center represents a major step forward
in the standardization process of the country's electronic
publications market.
</P>
<P>
Today's China Daily reported that the center, sponsored by the
Beijing Municipal Copyrights Protection Association, the center
will come under the close supervision and direction of the
Beijing Municipal Copyrights Bureau and the government of
Haidian District.
</P>
<P>
Covering an area of 2,000 square meters, the center sells
electronic publications and software products from 63 publishing
houses and computer companies.
</P>
<P>
Li Zhijun, Deputy Party Secretary of Beijing said that only
legally produced and quality electronic press products can obtain
access to the wholesale center.
</P>
<P>
Although China's total sales revenue reaches 843 million
U.S. dollars, the country's software market is still in its
infancy.
</P>
<P>
The lack of established sales channels and supervision
mechanism in the past decade has resulted in the spreading of
pirated and pornographic products in the past decade.
</P>
<P>
Shen Rengan, deputy director of the National Copyrights Bureau,
said big efforts have been made in the country to crack down on
illegal software products and electronic publications, yielding
marked progress.
</P>
<P>
He added that "but a fully developed and mature supervision
mechanism is an efficient measure int he campaign to standardize
the electronic press market." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
