<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Li Peng on Reform of State-Owned Enterprises (11) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 1 (Xinhua) -- To improve the economic
performance of China's state-owned sector, the Chinese government
will focus on rejuvenating large state-owned enterprises and
enterprise groups and giving small ones more freedom of operation,
</P>
<P>
Chinese Premier Li Peng made the remark in his government work
report delivered at the opening meeting of the Fifth Session of
the Eighth National People's Congress held here today.
</P>
<P>
With over 60 percent of state revenue deriving from state-owned
enterprises, two-thirds of all employees in cities and towns
working in state-owned enterprises, and with state-owned
enterprises dominating the fields of infrastructure, basic and
high technology industries, the premier said, the state sector of
the economy has made tremendous contributions to reform,
development and stability of the country.
</P>
<P>
However, Li pointed out, some state-owned enterprises face
difficulties and problems as a result of irrational management and
operational systems, and due to the impact of structural
readjustment.
</P>
<P>
"Since large state-owned enterprises are the backbone of the
national economy, the Central Government has decided to
concentrate first on rejuvenating 1,000 state-owned enterprises,"
the premier said.
</P>
<P>
Last year, banks provided financial support to approximately
300 of these enterprises and intensified supervision over the use
of these credit funds, achieving fairly good results, and the
government will extend that practice to 511 enterprises this year,
said Li.
</P>
<P>
He said that the government has been experimenting with 57
enterprise groups and will expand the experiment to 120 groups
this year in order to develop trans-regional and trans-industry
enterprise groups which combine industrial production,
technological development and trade. The reform measure is meant
to make them more competitive and stimulate other relevant
enterprises to develop, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970301.0262 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Li Peng on Reform of State-Owned Enterprises (12) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
He said,"These selected enterprise groups will enjoy more
decision-making power and will be entitled to import and export
independently, and we should take the initiative to accelerate and
standardize the reform aimed at establishing a joint stock system
in enterprises and promote their sound development."
</P>
<P>
He called for all localities and departments to cooperate with
each other and support key competitive enterprises which achieve
good economic returns.
</P>
<P>
The premier also mentioned that efforts should be made to make
a success of experiments on the establishment of state-owned
holding companies in aviation, petrochemical and non-ferrous
metals industries.
</P>
<P>
Systems of management in electric power, metallurgical and
other industries will also be reformed, he said.
</P>
<P>
Talking about smaller enterprises, Li said that most of the
more than 240,000 small state-owned enterprises throughout the
country are managed by city and county governments and reform is
carried out under the guidance of those governments.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, the premier noted, some localities have
revitalized a large number of these enterprises through
re-organization, association, merger, joint stock partnership,
leasing, contract operation and sell-off.
</P>
<P>
"This year we shall quicken the pace of reform in this regard,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Li told the deputies that joint stock partnership has been
introduced into small state-owned enterprises in some areas,
allowing employees to hold some shares while other shares remain
public.
</P>
<P>
Admitting that the practice is beneficial to the
re-organization and upgrading of enterprises and helps change the
way they operate, the premier nevertheless stressed that great
attention should be paid to tightening the examination and
assessment of state assets to prevent losses.  
</P>
</TEXT>
