<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Li Peng on Reducing Debts for State-Owned Enterprises (14) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 1 (Xinhua) -- The unduly high rate of debt in
China's state-owned enterprises is an important factor sapping
their vitality, and the government will adopt a series of policies
and measures to assist them in reducing their debts, said a top
Chinese leader today.
</P>
<P>
Li Peng, premier of the State Council, said the government will
gradually write off debts enterprises have incurred when
government appropriations have become loans, by converting them
into state capital funds in the enterprises.
</P>
<P>
In his government work report delivered at the Fifth Session of
the Eighth National People's Congress (NPC), he said the
conversion will be completed in the coal, water conservancy,
hydropower and defense industries this year. Other industries
should lose no time in doing the same, he said.
</P>
<P>
Secondly, the government will write off debts enterprises have
incurred since they began receiving capital construction operating
funds from the government in 1989 by gradually converting them
into state capital funds in the enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Thirdly, some large enterprises and enterprise groups will be
allowed to raise funds by issuing stocks or convertible bonds.
</P>
<P>
Fourthly, when conditions permit, local governments may use
local finance to support some of their key enterprises which are
insufficiently funded with capital.
</P>
<P>
Fifthly, enterprises should take the initiative to supplement
their accumulated funds and capital funds with their own financial
resources, make better use of these funds and reduce liabilities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970301.0266 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Help Eliminate Losses for State-Owned Enterprises (15) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 1 (Xinhua) -- The Central government and local
governments will continue to help enterprises under their charge
to eliminate losses for state-owned enterprises in an effort to
conscientiously strengthen the operation and management of
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Premier Li Peng made this remark in the Fifth Session of the
Eighth National People's Congress (NPC), which opened here today.
</P>
<P>
Scientific management is an important component in the
establishment of a modern enterprise system, and poor management
is a major factor contributing to current poor economic returns in
many enterprises, he said.
</P>
<P>
Li said enterprises should change their concepts, and truly
gear up production to market demand and establish a management
system which is responsive to the competitive environment.
</P>
<P>
Li urged the enterprises to handle well their basic work in a
down-to-earth manner, improve the management of production,
technology, operational costs, product quality, financial affairs
and marketing and speed up technological progress and provide
better after-sale services and expand their markets.
</P>
<P>
Competent administration is essential in revitalizing
enterprises, he said. It is, therefore, necessary to give top
priority to rectifying and improving enterprise administration.
This should be done by promoting to leading positions those who
have a pioneering spirit, are career-minded, good at operation and
management, and ready to share the joys and sorrows of other
employees.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese premier called on officials at various levels to
bear in mind the need to rely on the working class wholeheartedly,
strengthen democratic management and give full play to the role of
workers' conferences in democratic appraisal and supervision.
Efforts should also be made to pay great attention to safety in
production, tighten control over hidden perils and prevent and
reduce all kinds of accidents.
</P>
<P>
According to the premier, most of the enterprises which are
operating at a big loss or experiencing great difficulties belong
to the textile, coal, machinery, forestry and military industries.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, because the state has set quotas for subsidies
and provided loans at discounted interest rates, the coal industry
has actively diversified its operations, assisted surplus
employees to move on to other trades and reduced losses, thereby
achieving marked results.
</P>
<P>
Li noted this method will be tried out in other industries this
year as a means to extricate them from financial straits. He said
the Central Government and local governments will continue to be
responsible for helping the enterprises under their charge to
eliminate losses.
</P>
<P>
He said there exist a number of well-operated and well-managed
enterprises in various trades whose economic returns keep
increasing. "Their experience must be carefully summarized and
propagated," he said. "If more enterprises can outdo themselves
and even their counterparts in terms of economic returns, the
state sector of the economy will greatly improve."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
