<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Africa's Oldest Rally to Set Off in Nairobi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, February 28 (Xinhua) -- The Safari Rally, the oldest
in Africa and one of the toughest automobile races in world, is
slated to set off here on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
With a history of 44 years, the Safari Rally of the year
attracts 93 competitors for a whole distance of 2,349 kilometers
over mountains, savannas, rocks and hairpin bends.
</P>
<P>
Used to take place during the Easter holidays, the rally has
been pushed up to early March under new International Automobile
Federation regulations.
</P>
<P>
And penalty system is also to be changed in order to keep line
with other World Championship races.
</P>
<P>
The three-day race is divided into three legs with each sector
designated a specified time.
</P>
<P>
Originally, each minute a driver was late in completing a
sector counted as a loss of one point. But this year, drivers will
lose 10 seconds for every minute they are late.
</P>
<P>
Under the new and old penalty systems, the winner is the driver
with least penalty points.
</P>
<P>
Another new requirement prevent drivers from serving their cars
at any point but designated points along the course.
</P>
<P>
The Safari Rally, first staged in 1953, is now third on the
14-event World Championship calendar. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
