<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South China City to Charge Dog Raisers Large Fees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANTOU, March 1 (Xinhua) -- Dog raising will become a very
expensive hobby for residents of south China's Shantou City
as a result of the local government's attempts to reduce
dog-biting cases by charging dog keepers huge fees.
</P>
<P>
A set of regulations on restricting keeping dogs, which was
approved by the standing committee of the ninth Municipal People's
Congress, the local legislative body, went into effect as from
today.
</P>
<P>
Dog owners who live in major urban areas will have to pay local
police departments 10,000 yuan (about 1,200 US dollars) each as a
registration fee and 3,000 yuan in annual examination fee, which
far exceeds an ordinary wage-earner's income, for each dog.
</P>
<P>
Those in other areas of the city will have to pay 5,000 yuan
and 1,000 yuan per dog, respectively.
</P>
<P>
Dog walkers must now keep their pets on leads, while savage dogs
are not allowed to be taken to public places, according to the
regulation.
</P>
<P>
Shantou, one of five Special Economic Zones (SEZ) in China, is
China's fourth city to officially restrict the raising of dogs in
urban areas by charging enormous license fees, following Beijing,
Shanghai and Guangzhou.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, more and more well-off Shantou people have
taken to raising dogs and other pets.
</P>
<P>
"However, some dogs harm public hygiene and are even a danger
to people," the regulation says.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
