<HEADLINE> Coffee Futures Jump to 28-Month Highs in N.Y. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, February 28 (Xinhua) -- Coffee futures prices in New
York soared Friday to the highest level since October 1994 as
concern about dwindling supplies still lingered over the market.
</P>
<P>
Green, Arabica coffee for May delivery rose 5.75 cents to 1.768
U.S. dollars a pound on New York's Coffee, Sugar &AMP; Cocoa Exchange;
the March contract rose 7.30 cents to 1.904 U.S. dollars a pound,
the highest since October 26, 1994.
</P>
<P>
There have been reports that Brazilian coffee fields could
yield 27.5 million 132-pound bags of coffee this year, higher than
previous estimates of a 20 million bag crop. Some even predicted
the harvest would fall as low as 17 million bags.
</P>
<P>
But investors still worried about the quality of coffee beans
for this year and pushed prices higher.  
</P>
</TEXT>
