<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Young People Eye New Life </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, March 1 (Xinhua) -- A recent survey in Shanghai
showed that the young people here in China's largest city are more
broad-minded and career-minded and see eye to eye with their
international counterparts about life and work.
</P>
<P>
Facing reality and pursuing personal interests has become a new
fad among the city's six million people aged 15 to 39, about 45
percent of urban residents.
</P>
<P>
In response to the question of "What do you think is the most
respectable way to life?" 44.5 percent of those surveyed said
they prefer to live in accordance with their individual interests.
</P>
<P>
Just over 65 percent said they want to live according to their
own will, showing an amazing similarity to statistics among the
same group of people internationally.
</P>
<P>
Most of Shanghai's young people like to eat out in
fashionable, neat, but inexpensive restaurants rather than in
crowded and untidy snack bars that line the city's lanes.
</P>
<P>
Also like many other foreign young people, 66.13 percent of
Shanghai's younger people said they favor a job that combines a
sense of responsibility with hard but challenging work.
</P>
<P>
More closer economic ties with the outside world have made the
city's young people aware of different cultures. International
marriages probably reflect this trend of cultural exchanges.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
