<HEADLINE> Senior U.S. Official Visits Europe for NATO Affairs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 28 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Deputy Secretary of
State Strobe Talbot will start a five-day visit to Europe Monday
on the enlargement of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization
(NATO).
</P>
<P>
Talbot will go to Paris, Brussels and Moscow to talk about
NATO's reform, expansion, and relationship between the alliance
and Russia, U.S. State Department spokesman Nicholas Burns
announced today.
</P>
<P>
"He'll be consulting with the French government, with our NATO
allies in Brussels and with the Russian government about...all of
the issues that Secretary Albright dealt with in her recent trip
to the six capitals of Europe," he said.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Secretary of State Madelaine Albright had not achieved any
breakthrough on all the issues relating NATO during her trip to
Europe more than one week ago.
</P>
<P>
Russia is strongly opposed to the eastward expansion of NATO
and demands a legally binding document be signed between the two
sides while the U.S. prefers a non-binding one. 
</P>
