<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Trying to Break More Trade Barriers with Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 28 (Xinhua) -- After some breakthroughs in
the trade wars with Japan, President Clinton will seek elimination
of more barriers in a second term, U.S. Deputy Treasury Secretary
Lawrence Summers said today.
</P>
<P>
Calling Japan a "uniquely difficult place for foreign firms to
compete," Summers said the U.S. government did not plan to relent
in its efforts to attack unfair Japanese trade practices both
before the World Trade Organization (WTO) and in direct
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
"Japan's credibility in the United States and with its other
major trading partners as well depends on following through on its
commitments," he said.
</P>
<P>
He warned that U.S. government has "an elaborate process in
place to monitor these agreements" and U.S. "will continue to see
that they live up to the initial promise."
</P>
<P>
Japan has said that the WTO is the proper place for U.S.-Japan
trade disputes rather than head-to-head talks.
</P>
<P>
But Summers said while the WTO would be the proper venue for
many disputes, "wherever necessary, we will be prepared to pursue
our interest directly with the Japanese government."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Summers said the Clinton administration's policy
aims with Japan over the next four years would also focus on
prodding the Japanese government to continue efforts to spur its
sluggish economy by promoting increased domestic demand, rather
than exports, and to reforming its financial system.
</P>
<P>
Summers will travel to Tokyo next week for talks with Japanese
officials and lead a U.S. delegation to the first-ever meeting of
finance officials and central bank presidents from six Pacific Rim
countries and regions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
