<DOCNO> XIE19970301.0292 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Examines Role of Energy in Development, Environment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, February 28 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
Development Program (UNDP) on Friday released a report entilted
Energy After Rio: Prospects and Challenges, which examined the
critical role of energy in development and environment.
</P>
<P>
"No issue lies at the intersection of development and
environment, more prominently and uneasily than energy," said
James Gustave Speth, UNDP Administrator.
</P>
<P>
"I hope that his report can serve to foster the international
debate and consensus process concerning the importance of
sustainable energy and refocus international commitment on these
critical issues during the 1997 Review of Rio," he added.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, more than 1.5 billion people lack
access to electricity and two billion people still use traditional
fuels such as firewood and animal dung for cooking.
</P>
<P>
On the other side, fossil combustion today generates 76% of the
world's primary energy, the reliance of which has had severe
environmental consequences in the form of air pollution, acid rain
and increased atmospheric concentrations of greenhouse gases. With
consumption growth, the situation is getting worse, the report
warned.
</P>
<P>
Then what should be done? "Sustainable energy can be used as an
instrument for creating rural jobs, e.g. through bioenergy, and
new technologies offer opportunities for affordable and vastly
improved energy services," said Thomas B. Johansson, Director of
the UNDP Energy and Atmosphere Program.
</P>
<P>
Increased access to energy is essential to providing improved
health care, education, housing, water and sanitation services for
people living in poverty, the report said. Decentralized sources
of electricity would make possible entrepreneurial and small-scale
business ventures, the report added.
</P>
<P>
"Wind power is technologically ready to be deployed as a major
option for providing electricity," said the report. Photovoltaic
cells in small-scale, stand-alone power applications and solar
thermal electric power today provide important renewable energy
supply options. Fuel cell, devices that convert hydrogen fuel
directly into electricity without first burning it to produce
heat, offer high thermodynamic efficiency, low maintenance
requirement, and zero or near-zero pollutant emissions.
</P>
<P>
Noting that the annual energy investment requirements worldwide
are projected to rise to 750 billion U.S. dollars by the year
2020, up from 450 billion U.S. dollars, the reports said that
renewable and higher efficiency energy systems would enable
developing countries to meet their growing energy needs at a lower
cost.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970301.0293 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Burns: Shanghai Communique Is A Milestone in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 28 (Xinhua) -- Spokesman of the U.S. State
Department Nicholas Burns said today that the first Sino-U.S.
Communique, known as the Shanghai Communique, was "a key
milestone" in U.S. relations with China.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press briefing, Burns said that the Shanghai
Communique and the other two communiques the United States signed
with China are "the foundation of U.S.-China relations".
</P>
<P>
Today is the 25th anniversary of The Shanghai Communique, which
opened up the path to the normalization of relations between China
and the United States. The communique laid down the principles for
relations between the two countries with different social systems
and ideology.
</P>
<P>
Burns said that since the signing of Shanghai Communique in
1972, the relationship between the United States and China "has
become significantly deeper and more extensive."
</P>
<P>
"For the future, we need to work to build a more constructive
relationship with China," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We look forward to a schedule of high-level visits during 1997
and 1998, and we hope to build on the record of the past to
achieve a more stable footing for U.S.-China relations over the
next several years, certainly more stable that we have had in the
last several years," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
