<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Asks Russia to Return Archives Moscow Keeps </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, February 28 (Xinhua) -- France today asked Russia to
return the French archives it has kept since the end of World War
II, but said that it is not clear how many objects of arts France
lost during the war are in Russia.
</P>
<P>
"Concerning the French public and private archives kept in
Moscow in the wake of World War II, the French government asks the
Russian government in a constant way that the application of the
agreement of restitution concluded on November 12, 1992, should be
resumed and carried through," said French Foreign Ministry vice
spokesman Yves Doutriaux.
</P>
<P>
He said that French Foreign Minister Herve de Charette raised
the issue recently with his Russian counterpart, Yevgeny Primakov.
</P>
<P>
The French archives were first robbed by Nazis from France, and
were then seized and brought home by the Soviet troops from
Germany at the end of World War II.
</P>
<P>
"In absence of all publicity from the Russian authorities of a
list of their `war trophies,' France does not have any knowledge
of the presence on the territory of the Russian Federation of
clearly identified French works of arts," said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The local daily Le Figaro said today that some French cultural
properties robbed by Nazis and then seized by the Soviet troops
are now lying in "the cellars of Russian museums."
</P>
<P>
The daily said that France does not want to raise the issue
with Russia, because it does not want to add one more dispute with
Moscow besides that over NATO expansion.
</P>
<P>
The Russian State Duma voted in early February that all
cultural properties seized by Soviet troops during World War II
are Russian properties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
