<HEADLINE> Stocks Continue Sliding on Wall Street </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, February 28 (Xinhua) -- New York stocks fell today
for the third straight session, weighed down again by fears the
Federal Reserve may soon raise interest rates to check inflation.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average lost 47.33 points to 6,877.74.
The blue-chip barometer decline about 160 points over the past
three sessions.
</P>
<P>
Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 4-to-3 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
Broader measures also fell, although the Nasdaq composite index
suffered more smaller losses as several computer-industry shares
started to recover.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume totaled 508.27 million shares as against 464.67
million in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock list fell 3.66 at 1,309.00, and
the NYSE composite index fell 2.38 at 415.51.
</P>
<P>
The Nasdaq composite index fell 3.66 to 1,309.00, and the
American Stock Exchange composite index fell 0.93 to 594.24.
</P>
<P>
Stocks have been retreating with bonds since Wednesday, when Fed
chairman Alan Greenspan warned sternly that the stock market's
stunning advance poses an inflationary risk. Greenspan, in a report
to Congress, cautioned that the central bank may increase interest
rates even before a measurable increase in inflation is evident.
</P>
<P>
The concerns over a Fed rate hike continued today after another
Fed official issued some more cautionary comments.
</P>
<P>
Bond prices steadied after a two-day pullback, leaving the yield
on the 30-year Treasury unchanged at 6.80 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Dow's weakest issues were J.P. Morgan, General Electric, and
Chevron.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
