<HEADLINE> Clinton Recertifies Mexico as Anti-drug Ally </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 28 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
today decided to recertify Mexico as a fully cooperating ally in
fighting against narcotics smuggling, the Associated Press
reported.
</P>
<P>
"The decision to certify Mexico was recommended unanimously by
top Clinton aides from the State, Defense, Justice and Treasury
departments and the National Security Council," the news agency
quoted a senior official as saying.
</P>
<P>
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, who had a late morning
meeting Friday with Clinton on the matter, was expected to
formally announce the decision later today.
</P>
<P>
Clinton was acting on the eve of the congressionally mandated
deadline for evaluating the anti-narcotics records of dozens of
drug source and drug transit countries.
</P>
<P>
Clinton made the recertification despite 40 Congressmen demand
for decertification after Mexico had unearthed corruption in the
anti-drug battle.
</P>
<P>
Mexican officials had warned that decertification could lead to
reduced cooperation on anti-narcotics cooperation with the United
States.
</P>
<P>
Clinton also renewed for another year his 1996 decision not to
certify the counter-narcotics program of Colombia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
