<DOCNO> XIE19970301.0298 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Recertifies Mexico as Anti-drug Ally </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 28 (Xinhua) -- Despite some congressional
opposition, U.S. President Bill Clinton today recertified Mexico
as a fully cooperating ally in the battle against drug smuggling.
</P>
<P>
Clinton also renewed for another year his 1996 decision not to
certify the counter-narcotics program of Colombia.
</P>
<P>
Clinton's decisions were announced by Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright this afternoon at a State Department news
conference after meeting with Clinton..
</P>
<P>
Clinton chose to recertify Mexico "with firm expectations of
further progress in the near term," Albright said.
</P>
<P>
But she added that Mexico's anti-drug effort would be
constantly monitored by senior administration officials.
</P>
<P>
Some 40 Congressmen signed a letter to Clinton urging
decertification after Mexico unearthed corruption in the battle
against drugs. But Mexican officials warned that such a decision
could lead to reduced on anti-drug cooperation with the United
States.
</P>
<P>
The decision to deny certification to Colombia was based on a
judgment that "corruption remains rampant at the highest levels of
the Colombian government," Albright said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton was acting on the eve of the congressionally mandated
deadline for evaluating the anti-narcotics records of dozens of
drug source and drug transit countries.
</P>
<P>
Mexico was among the 23 countries or regions that Clinton has
given certifications. But Clinton decertified Colombia,
Afghanistan, Burma, Nigeria, Syria and Iran and granted Belize,
Lebanon and Pakistan a waiver. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970301.0299 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Intl Conference on Land Mines Ends </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, February 28 (Xinhua) -- The four-day International
Conference on Land-mines ended here today as delegates urged all
governments to make formal pledges for the total ban on mines.
</P>
<P>
A final declaration issued by the conference also urged the
International Campaign for the Ban on Mines, all governments and
relative non-governmental organizations, to actively participate
in the negotiation process aimed at signing a treaty to ban the
production, sales, use and transfer of mines worldwide.
</P>
<P>
It called for creating a mine-free area in southern Africa
which is among the regions worst hit by the land mines in the
world.
</P>
<P>
African countries should abide by all the resolutions passed
by the Organization of African Unity (OAU) concerning the ban on
mines in the continent, said the declaration.
</P>
<P>
It also called on African states to follow the step of the
Mozambican government which on Wednesday declared a ban on the
use, storage and transfer of mines in the country.
</P>
<P>
Julio Mapote, coordinator of the Mozambican Anti-Mine
Campaign, said the basic objectives of the conference have been
met while noting that it is not enough to just sign an agreement,
which must be followed by concrete measures to implement it.
</P>
<P>
He said the meeting, organized and attended mainly by
non-governmental organizations, is a way to bridge a dialogue
between the civil society and the government to bring consensus
on the mine issue.
</P>
<P>
The conference have been attended by 400 delegates from 60
countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
